Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.46,0:00:25.55,Default,,0,0,0,,After watching the 2020 regional convention
Dialogue: 0,0:00:25.55,0:00:27.92,Default,,0,0,0,,in her native language of Chichewa,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.92,0:00:32.34,Default,,0,0,0,,16-year-old Lisa from Malawi stated:
Dialogue: 0,0:00:32.34,0:00:37.31,Default,,0,0,0,,“With this convention, I saw\Nhow Jehovah fulfilled his promise
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.31,0:00:40.14,Default,,0,0,0,,“at Hebrews 13:5:
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.14,0:00:44.65,Default,,0,0,0,,‘I will never leave you,\Nand I will never abandon you.’”
Dialogue: 0,0:00:45.86,0:00:48.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Many have made\Nsimilar appreciative comments
Dialogue: 0,0:00:48.69,0:00:51.91,Default,,0,0,0,,after watching the convention\Nin their language.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:51.91,0:00:54.66,Default,,0,0,0,,You have made kind donations online
Dialogue: 0,0:00:54.66,0:00:57.83,Default,,0,0,0,,at donate.jw.org
Dialogue: 0,0:00:57.83,0:01:00.04,Default,,0,0,0,,and by other means.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:00.04,0:01:02.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you for these donations
Dialogue: 0,0:01:02.63,0:01:05.96,Default,,0,0,0,,that support\Nour extensive translation efforts.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:07.80,0:01:12.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Earlier in our program,\Nwe discussed five peace wreckers
Dialogue: 0,0:01:12.47,0:01:14.47,Default,,0,0,0,,that we should “put away.”
Dialogue: 0,0:01:14.47,0:01:18.56,Default,,0,0,0,,But what can we do\Nif peace has been disturbed?
Dialogue: 0,0:01:18.56,0:01:23.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Can it be restored, and if so, how?
Dialogue: 0,0:01:23.02,0:01:25.81,Default,,0,0,0,,We invite you to pay careful attention
Dialogue: 0,0:01:25.81,0:01:29.07,Default,,0,0,0,,to the following four-part symposium.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:29.07,0:01:33.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Brother John Ekrann, a helper\Nto the Coordinators’ Committee,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:33.03,0:01:35.66,Default,,0,0,0,,will start us off with the talk
Dialogue: 0,0:01:35.66,0:01:38.66,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Seek Peace and Pursue It’ . . .
Dialogue: 0,0:01:38.66,0:01:41.37,Default,,0,0,0,,By Not Quickly Taking Offense.”
Dialogue: 0,0:01:49.30,0:01:54.30,Default,,0,0,0,,The title of this series of four talks\Nis “Seek Peace and Pursue It,”
Dialogue: 0,0:01:54.30,0:01:58.18,Default,,0,0,0,,and it’s based on 1 Peter 3:11.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:58.18,0:02:00.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s read that together
Dialogue: 0,0:02:00.43,0:02:03.81,Default,,0,0,0,,—1 Peter 3:11:
Dialogue: 0,0:02:05.48,0:02:09.86,Default,,0,0,0,,“Let him turn away from what is bad\Nand do what is good;
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.86,0:02:14.86,Default,,0,0,0,,let him seek peace and pursue it.”
Dialogue: 0,0:02:14.86,0:02:19.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, we have to pursue peace,\Nand pursuit requires effort.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.79,0:02:24.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Have you ever had to chase a piece\Nof paper that was in your hands
Dialogue: 0,0:02:24.33,0:02:26.50,Default,,0,0,0,,and got blown away by the wind,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:26.50,0:02:30.67,Default,,0,0,0,,and just once you get to it,\Nthe wind blows it away again and again?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.67,0:02:32.84,Default,,0,0,0,,It can really take quite some effort
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.84,0:02:36.72,Default,,0,0,0,,to retrieve and get that paper\Nback in your hands.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:36.72,0:02:41.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Just standing there and watching\Nthe paper blow farther and farther away
Dialogue: 0,0:02:41.72,0:02:44.77,Default,,0,0,0,,is not going to get it back.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.77,0:02:47.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, peace can be a lot like that paper.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:47.60,0:02:50.61,Default,,0,0,0,,At some point, it can get blown away,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:50.61,0:02:52.74,Default,,0,0,0,,and we have to then chase,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:52.74,0:02:57.74,Default,,0,0,0,,or pursue, it to get that peace back again.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:57.74,0:03:02.75,Default,,0,0,0,,This series of talks will help us\Nto pursue peace in four ways:
Dialogue: 0,0:03:02.75,0:03:06.00,Default,,0,0,0,,by not quickly taking offense,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:06.00,0:03:08.38,Default,,0,0,0,,by apologizing,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:08.38,0:03:10.79,Default,,0,0,0,,by forgiving freely,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.79,0:03:14.01,Default,,0,0,0,,and by using our gift of speech wisely.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.80,0:03:18.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s consider our first way to pursue peace:
Dialogue: 0,0:03:18.64,0:03:23.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Avoid quickly taking offense.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.52,0:03:25.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, because we are imperfect,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:25.85,0:03:29.69,Default,,0,0,0,,we might misjudge others\Nand quickly take offense.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:29.69,0:03:32.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Notice that we say quickly take offense.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:32.27,0:03:34.28,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s an important word.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:34.28,0:03:37.61,Default,,0,0,0,,We need to avoid jumping\Nto conclusions quickly
Dialogue: 0,0:03:37.61,0:03:41.66,Default,,0,0,0,,before we actually have the facts.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:41.66,0:03:46.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Even faithful men like Jesus’ apostles\Nhave taken offense too quickly.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.66,0:03:49.63,Default,,0,0,0,,You may recall the time that Jesus\Nand his apostles
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.63,0:03:52.84,Default,,0,0,0,,were looking for lodging\Nin a Samaritan village.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:52.84,0:03:57.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, the Samaritans in that village\Nrudely denied them lodging.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:57.84,0:04:02.51,Default,,0,0,0,,At Luke 9:54-56,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:02.51,0:04:05.43,Default,,0,0,0,,the apostles—James and John—\Nsay to Jesus:
Dialogue: 0,0:04:05.43,0:04:10.44,Default,,0,0,0,,“Lord, do you want us to call fire down\Nfrom heaven and annihilate them?”
Dialogue: 0,0:04:11.73,0:04:16.15,Default,,0,0,0,,But Jesus rebukes them for their\Nrash and rather violent suggestion.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:17.78,0:04:19.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Think of the serious consequences
Dialogue: 0,0:04:19.91,0:04:24.58,Default,,0,0,0,,had Jesus yielded to the violent temper\Nof James and John.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:24.58,0:04:29.29,Default,,0,0,0,,The Samaritans could have become\Nprejudiced against the Kingdom message.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:29.29,0:04:33.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Instead, Jesus pursues a peaceful solution.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.79,0:04:38.63,Default,,0,0,0,,The account says\N‘they simply went to a different village.’
Dialogue: 0,0:04:38.63,0:04:42.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, does this mean we’re saying\Nwe can never take offense?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:42.59,0:04:46.68,Default,,0,0,0,,No, you may have a legitimate\N“cause for complaint.”
Dialogue: 0,0:04:46.68,0:04:51.69,Default,,0,0,0,,The key point is that we should not\Nquickly draw conclusions
Dialogue: 0,0:04:51.69,0:04:55.11,Default,,0,0,0,,before we hear all the facts.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:55.11,0:04:58.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Proverbs 18:13 says:
Dialogue: 0,0:04:58.86,0:05:03.03,Default,,0,0,0,,“When anyone replies to a matter\Nbefore he hears the facts,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.03,0:05:05.78,Default,,0,0,0,,it is foolish and humiliating.”
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.20,0:05:09.20,Default,,0,0,0,,In the following dramatization,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:09.20,0:05:13.08,Default,,0,0,0,,note what helps one sister\Nto overlook an offense.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:15.21,0:05:17.55,Default,,0,0,0,,And I expected more from you.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:17.55,0:05:19.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Haley, what are you talking about?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:19.84,0:05:23.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Gossiping about my posts!
Dialogue: 0,0:05:23.30,0:05:26.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you that lonely\Nthat you’ve got nothing better to do?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:30.31,0:05:32.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Haley,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.44,0:05:37.19,Default,,0,0,0,,wait, please!
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.19,0:05:38.57,Default,,0,0,0,,I don’t know what’s happening.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:39.28,0:05:41.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Did you talk to Emily about my posts?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:41.90,0:05:43.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, we did . . .
Dialogue: 0,0:05:43.16,0:05:44.82,Default,,0,0,0,,So you gossiped about me.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:44.82,0:05:45.82,Default,,0,0,0,,No, I would . . .
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.82,0:05:47.33,Default,,0,0,0,,I looked up to you!
Dialogue: 0,0:05:47.33,0:05:47.99,Default,,0,0,0,,I would never . . .
Dialogue: 0,0:05:47.99,0:05:49.41,Default,,0,0,0,,You’re supposed to be the mature one,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:49.41,0:05:51.58,Default,,0,0,0,,and you’re just like Emily,\Nbusy running your mouth.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.58,0:05:52.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Haley!
Dialogue: 0,0:05:53.50,0:05:57.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Look, I can see you’re upset,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:57.09,0:05:59.67,Default,,0,0,0,,but trust me,\Nthis is a huge misunderstanding.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.18,0:06:05.80,Default,,0,0,0,,I love you.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:05.80,0:06:10.22,Default,,0,0,0,,I would never ever say anything\Nbehind your back.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:10.85,0:06:14.19,Default,,0,0,0,,So please calm down.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:19.40,0:06:23.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Sometimes I just feel so alone
Dialogue: 0,0:06:26.45,0:06:28.87,Default,,0,0,0,,—between Nana and work—
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.33,0:06:34.41,Default,,0,0,0,,and then knowing all of you\Nare talking about me.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.62,0:06:38.96,Default,,0,0,0,,I promise, that’s not what happened.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.42,0:06:44.09,Default,,0,0,0,,You’re just really tired and overwhelmed.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:45.88,0:06:48.60,Default,,0,0,0,,So why don’t we\Njust slow things down a little.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:50.22,0:06:54.31,Default,,0,0,0,,You know, meetings\Nalways make me feel better,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:54.31,0:06:56.44,Default,,0,0,0,,even on my worst days.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:58.23,0:07:00.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Why don’t we go inside,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:00.52,0:07:03.57,Default,,0,0,0,,clean up a little,\Nand enjoy the program together.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.53,0:07:07.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Then afterward, we can all talk.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:08.32,0:07:11.20,Default,,0,0,0,,I promise, it’ll be OK.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:16.96,0:07:19.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Haley really was upset.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:19.38,0:07:23.88,Default,,0,0,0,,She had already concluded that she\Nwas being gossiped about by everyone.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:25.13,0:07:28.30,Default,,0,0,0,,If we find ourselves\Nlike Haley feeling offended,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:28.30,0:07:32.60,Default,,0,0,0,,how can we avoid quickly taking offense?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:32.60,0:07:36.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we must stop and think.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:36.31,0:07:39.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s read Ecclesiastes 7:9
Dialogue: 0,0:07:39.35,0:07:42.94,Default,,0,0,0,,for some very good advice\Nin these situations
Dialogue: 0,0:07:42.94,0:07:46.40,Default,,0,0,0,,—Ecclesiastes 7:9:
Dialogue: 0,0:07:46.40,0:07:49.57,Default,,0,0,0,,“Do not be quick to take offense,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:49.57,0:07:54.12,Default,,0,0,0,,for the taking of offense lodges\Nin the bosom of fools.”
Dialogue: 0,0:07:55.66,0:07:58.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Like Celia said in the parking lot to Haley,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:58.83,0:08:01.34,Default,,0,0,0,,“Please calm down.”
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.34,0:08:03.46,Default,,0,0,0,,So in those situations,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.46,0:08:05.71,Default,,0,0,0,,you need to think about what you know
Dialogue: 0,0:08:05.71,0:08:09.18,Default,,0,0,0,,and, just as important, what you don’t know.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:09.18,0:08:12.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, you know what you were told happened,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:12.26,0:08:15.18,Default,,0,0,0,,but what was really said?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:15.18,0:08:18.81,Default,,0,0,0,,In the video,\NHaley quickly believed what she was told.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:18.81,0:08:22.27,Default,,0,0,0,,She did not even ask Celia\Nwhat she really said.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:23.52,0:08:25.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Or you may know what was said,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:25.82,0:08:29.91,Default,,0,0,0,,but do you know what was\Nreally meant by it?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.91,0:08:32.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Haley asked,\N“Did you talk about . . . my posts?”
Dialogue: 0,0:08:32.82,0:08:34.83,Default,,0,0,0,,And Celia said, “Yes.”
Dialogue: 0,0:08:34.83,0:08:37.70,Default,,0,0,0,,And immediately, Haley assumed the worst.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:39.33,0:08:43.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Or perhaps we misjudged\Nthe person who hurt us.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:43.67,0:08:47.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Haley misjudged Celia\Non the spot by saying,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.88,0:08:50.38,Default,,0,0,0,,‘You’re just as bad as Emily.’
Dialogue: 0,0:08:50.38,0:08:52.89,Default,,0,0,0,,She had not even heard from Celia yet.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:54.30,0:08:57.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Haley said to Celia\Nthat she was the mature one,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:57.02,0:08:59.02,Default,,0,0,0,,the one she looked up to,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.02,0:09:02.90,Default,,0,0,0,,yet she was quick to believe\Nthe worst about her.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:02.90,0:09:06.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Haley had not stopped\Nand really thought about what
Dialogue: 0,0:09:06.32,0:09:08.32,Default,,0,0,0,,she was thinking and saying.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.65,0:09:12.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Perhaps she was having a hard day.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:12.99,0:09:16.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, Celia really set a fine example for us.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:16.49,0:09:19.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Even though Haley spoke harshly to her,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:19.45,0:09:22.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Celia was calm and listened to Haley.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:22.87,0:09:25.71,Default,,0,0,0,,As Haley explained how\Nshe was feeling lonely,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:25.71,0:09:28.09,Default,,0,0,0,,dealing and caring for her grandmother,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:28.09,0:09:32.01,Default,,0,0,0,,you can see the love and concern\Nthat Celia had for Haley,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:32.01,0:09:36.39,Default,,0,0,0,,even though just moments before\Nshe had spoken really harshly to her.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:37.68,0:09:41.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, besides taking time\Nto think things through,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.35,0:09:45.86,Default,,0,0,0,,we also need to remember\Nthat it is Jehovah’s opinion of us
Dialogue: 0,0:09:45.86,0:09:48.36,Default,,0,0,0,,that matters the most.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:48.36,0:09:51.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, that’s an important point,\Nespecially when we deal
Dialogue: 0,0:09:51.78,0:09:54.95,Default,,0,0,0,,with misunderstandings\Nor false accusations.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.20,0:10:00.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Think about it:\NJehovah is an eyewitness to everything.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:01.62,0:10:04.54,Default,,0,0,0,,To illustrate that, I want you to imagine
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.54,0:10:06.54,Default,,0,0,0,,you had a traffic accident.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:06.54,0:10:09.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, you were just sitting at the stop sign,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:09.00,0:10:13.01,Default,,0,0,0,,but another car ran straight into you.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:13.01,0:10:16.68,Default,,0,0,0,,The police come,\Nand the person that ran into you
Dialogue: 0,0:10:16.68,0:10:21.56,Default,,0,0,0,,says that you ran into them,\Nand the police believe them.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:22.64,0:10:25.06,Default,,0,0,0,,You take the matter to court.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:25.06,0:10:29.90,Default,,0,0,0,,The judge listens as the other person\Nsays that you ran into them;
Dialogue: 0,0:10:29.90,0:10:32.94,Default,,0,0,0,,however, before you can say anything,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:32.94,0:10:37.32,Default,,0,0,0,,the judge says:\N“No, that is not what happened.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:37.32,0:10:41.12,Default,,0,0,0,,“I was there walking on the sidewalk\Nacross the street that day,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:41.12,0:10:43.21,Default,,0,0,0,,and I saw the whole thing.”
Dialogue: 0,0:10:44.75,0:10:48.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, it’s extremely unlikely\Nthat you can go to court and expect
Dialogue: 0,0:10:48.50,0:10:51.96,Default,,0,0,0,,the judge for your case\Nto have been an eyewitness.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:51.96,0:10:55.22,Default,,0,0,0,,This does illustrate, though,\Nthe peace of mind that we can have
Dialogue: 0,0:10:55.22,0:10:59.72,Default,,0,0,0,,knowing that Jehovah is an eyewitness\Nto all that happens.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:00.76,0:11:04.81,Default,,0,0,0,,So when falsely accused\Nor when we have a misunderstanding
Dialogue: 0,0:11:04.81,0:11:09.77,Default,,0,0,0,,that we cannot seem to clear up,\Nit is of great comfort for us to know
Dialogue: 0,0:11:09.77,0:11:14.53,Default,,0,0,0,,that Jehovah was there that day\Nand saw the whole thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:16.53,0:11:19.78,Default,,0,0,0,,We don’t need to take offense\Nat every negative thing
Dialogue: 0,0:11:19.78,0:11:22.04,Default,,0,0,0,,that is said or done around us
Dialogue: 0,0:11:22.04,0:11:26.71,Default,,0,0,0,,or feel we have to defend ourselves\Nas being right on every occasion.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:27.71,0:11:30.54,Default,,0,0,0,,We would surely wear out emotionally
Dialogue: 0,0:11:30.54,0:11:34.67,Default,,0,0,0,,and probably not have very many friends.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:36.17,0:11:41.05,Default,,0,0,0,,We should be willing\Nto overlook minor transgressions.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:41.05,0:11:45.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s look at Proverbs 19:11
Dialogue: 0,0:11:45.93,0:11:49.15,Default,,0,0,0,,—Proverbs 19:11.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:49.15,0:11:52.15,Default,,0,0,0,,What can help us?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:52.15,0:11:57.15,Default,,0,0,0,,“The insight of a man\Ncertainly slows down his anger,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:57.15,0:12:02.16,Default,,0,0,0,,and it is beauty on his part\Nto overlook an offense.”
Dialogue: 0,0:12:03.58,0:12:07.08,Default,,0,0,0,,So can you “overlook an offense”?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:07.08,0:12:11.29,Default,,0,0,0,,As the proverb said,\Nthat ‘is beauty on our part.’
Dialogue: 0,0:12:11.29,0:12:14.67,Default,,0,0,0,,If not and you have\Na serious cause for complaint,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:14.67,0:12:18.30,Default,,0,0,0,,handle matters\Naccording to Jehovah’s direction.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:18.30,0:12:20.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Show insight.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:20.55,0:12:24.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Slow down any anger.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:24.06,0:12:27.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Think carefully, and listen patiently
Dialogue: 0,0:12:27.52,0:12:30.85,Default,,0,0,0,,to make sure you clearly have all the facts
Dialogue: 0,0:12:30.85,0:12:33.44,Default,,0,0,0,,before you become offended\Nor take action.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:35.23,0:12:37.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Remember that piece of paper\Nthat you had in your hands
Dialogue: 0,0:12:37.57,0:12:40.61,Default,,0,0,0,,and got blown away by the wind?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:40.61,0:12:44.20,Default,,0,0,0,,What if it was a hundred-dollar bill?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:44.20,0:12:46.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, you would make every effort
Dialogue: 0,0:12:46.45,0:12:50.46,Default,,0,0,0,,to pursue it and get it back\Nbecause it’s valuable.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:50.46,0:12:55.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Our peace with our brothers\Nis far more valuable than paper money.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:55.46,0:12:58.01,Default,,0,0,0,,When our peace\Nwith our brothers or sisters
Dialogue: 0,0:12:58.01,0:13:02.22,Default,,0,0,0,,is blown away\Nby misunderstandings, mistakes, or sin,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:02.22,0:13:06.47,Default,,0,0,0,,then we should pursue peace\Nand try hard to get it back.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:08.18,0:13:12.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, we glorify God and promote peace
Dialogue: 0,0:13:12.10,0:13:15.73,Default,,0,0,0,,when we avoid quickly taking offense.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:17.40,0:13:20.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Brother Ralph Walls,\Na helper to the Personnel Committee,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:20.32,0:13:23.53,Default,,0,0,0,,will now present the next talk\Nof this symposium,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:23.53,0:13:27.49,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Seek Peace and Pursue It’\N. . . By Apologizing.”
Dialogue: 0,0:13:35.54,0:13:38.92,Default,,0,0,0,,“I am so sorry.”
Dialogue: 0,0:13:38.92,0:13:42.38,Default,,0,0,0,,“It’s my fault, please forgive me.”
Dialogue: 0,0:13:42.38,0:13:44.39,Default,,0,0,0,,No matter how we phrase it,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:44.39,0:13:47.68,Default,,0,0,0,,it can be difficult to apologize.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.68,0:13:49.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Why is that so challenging?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:49.89,0:13:51.89,Default,,0,0,0,,There are many reasons:
Dialogue: 0,0:13:51.89,0:13:55.73,Default,,0,0,0,,We may fear confrontation,\Nblame, or rejection.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:55.73,0:13:59.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Perhaps we feel embarrassed,\Nand we’re too proud to apologize.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:59.36,0:14:04.24,Default,,0,0,0,,We may reason, ‘Apologizing will not undo\Nthe blunder I’ve already made.’
Dialogue: 0,0:14:04.24,0:14:07.62,Default,,0,0,0,,And it may even be that we are angry.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:08.66,0:14:11.37,Default,,0,0,0,,This is such a matter of concern
Dialogue: 0,0:14:11.37,0:14:14.50,Default,,0,0,0,,that “in July 2000,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:14.50,0:14:18.38,Default,,0,0,0,,“the California State Legislature\Nin the United States
Dialogue: 0,0:14:18.38,0:14:22.13,Default,,0,0,0,,“passed a bill designed\Nto relieve people of liability
Dialogue: 0,0:14:22.13,0:14:25.89,Default,,0,0,0,,“if they express sympathy to an individual\Nwho was injured in an accident
Dialogue: 0,0:14:25.89,0:14:28.76,Default,,0,0,0,,“in which they\Nthemselves were involved. . . .
Dialogue: 0,0:14:28.76,0:14:32.35,Default,,0,0,0,,“It was noted that . . . people\Noften hesitate to extend an apology
Dialogue: 0,0:14:32.35,0:14:35.65,Default,,0,0,0,,“[out of concern that]\Nit could be construed in court
Dialogue: 0,0:14:35.65,0:14:38.90,Default,,0,0,0,,as an admission of guilt.”
Dialogue: 0,0:14:38.90,0:14:42.74,Default,,0,0,0,,The Bible provides an account\Nof a faithful servant,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:42.74,0:14:44.74,Default,,0,0,0,,the apostle Paul,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:44.74,0:14:48.70,Default,,0,0,0,,who was a good example\Nof one who apologized.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:48.70,0:14:52.75,Default,,0,0,0,,The account is\Nin the book of Acts chapter 23.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:52.75,0:14:56.54,Default,,0,0,0,,The setting: A Roman military officer
Dialogue: 0,0:14:56.54,0:15:00.59,Default,,0,0,0,,wanted to know why Paul\Nwas being accused by the Jews.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:00.59,0:15:05.55,Default,,0,0,0,,So he brought Paul\Nto the Jewish chief priests
Dialogue: 0,0:15:05.55,0:15:09.68,Default,,0,0,0,,and commanded the Sanhedrin,\Nthe high court, to assemble.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:09.68,0:15:13.77,Default,,0,0,0,,As we read Acts 23:1-5 together,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:13.77,0:15:16.14,Default,,0,0,0,,we can’t help but be impressed
Dialogue: 0,0:15:16.14,0:15:20.02,Default,,0,0,0,,by Paul’s boldness\Nas he stands for what is right.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:20.02,0:15:24.36,Default,,0,0,0,,But at the same time,\Nplease take note of his humility.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:25.99,0:15:30.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Acts 23:1: “Looking intently\Nat the Sanhedrin,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:30.83,0:15:34.62,Default,,0,0,0,,“Paul said: ‘Men, brothers,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:34.62,0:15:36.71,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘I have behaved before God
Dialogue: 0,0:15:36.71,0:15:40.59,Default,,0,0,0,,“with a perfectly clear conscience\Ndown to this day.’
Dialogue: 0,0:15:40.59,0:15:42.71,Default,,0,0,0,,“At this the high priest Ananias
Dialogue: 0,0:15:42.71,0:15:46.88,Default,,0,0,0,,“ordered those standing by him\Nto strike him on the mouth.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:46.88,0:15:48.89,Default,,0,0,0,,“Then Paul said to him:
Dialogue: 0,0:15:48.89,0:15:52.72,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘God is going to strike you,\Nyou whitewashed wall.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:52.72,0:15:55.27,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Do you sit to judge me according to the Law
Dialogue: 0,0:15:55.27,0:15:57.56,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and at the same time violate the Law
Dialogue: 0,0:15:57.56,0:16:00.56,Default,,0,0,0,,“by commanding me to be struck?’
Dialogue: 0,0:16:00.56,0:16:02.94,Default,,0,0,0,,“Those standing by said:
Dialogue: 0,0:16:02.94,0:16:06.36,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Are you insulting the high priest of God?’
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.74,0:16:10.28,Default,,0,0,0,,“And Paul said: ‘Brothers,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:10.28,0:16:13.08,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘I did not know he was high priest.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:13.08,0:16:16.83,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘For it is written,\N“You must not speak injuriously
Dialogue: 0,0:16:16.83,0:16:18.83,Default,,0,0,0,,of a ruler of your people.”’”
Dialogue: 0,0:16:20.12,0:16:23.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul immediately admitted his error.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:23.17,0:16:25.17,Default,,0,0,0,,What he had said,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:25.17,0:16:29.88,Default,,0,0,0,,that the one appointed as judge\Nshould not resort to violence, was right.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:29.88,0:16:32.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Yet, he apologized.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:33.64,0:16:35.93,Default,,0,0,0,,In the following dramatization,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:35.93,0:16:37.93,Default,,0,0,0,,we will see an older sister
Dialogue: 0,0:16:37.93,0:16:42.61,Default,,0,0,0,,applying the inspired words of Titus 2:3-5
Dialogue: 0,0:16:42.61,0:16:46.86,Default,,0,0,0,,in order to advise younger sisters\N“to be sound in mind.”
Dialogue: 0,0:16:46.86,0:16:50.15,Default,,0,0,0,,We will also observe\Nhow one of the younger sisters
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.15,0:16:53.91,Default,,0,0,0,,avoids further problems\Nand pursues peace
Dialogue: 0,0:16:53.91,0:16:55.95,Default,,0,0,0,,by humbly apologizing.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:05.13,0:17:07.21,Default,,0,0,0,,I don’t know how this happened
Dialogue: 0,0:17:09.42,0:17:13.22,Default,,0,0,0,,but, Haley, I’m sorry.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:13.22,0:17:15.97,Default,,0,0,0,,It hurts me to see you so upset.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:20.44,0:17:23.06,Default,,0,0,0,,I can’t believe you two.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:23.06,0:17:25.06,Default,,0,0,0,,First,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:26.27,0:17:28.28,Default,,0,0,0,,what you heard
Dialogue: 0,0:17:29.44,0:17:33.24,Default,,0,0,0,,was not what I said.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.24,0:17:35.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, I thought that was how you felt.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:37.79,0:17:41.29,Default,,0,0,0,,And even if I got that part wrong,\Nall this drama?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:41.29,0:17:42.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Now stop!
Dialogue: 0,0:17:44.58,0:17:46.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Come on, girls.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:47.75,0:17:49.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Haley, come closer.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:59.39,0:18:04.40,Default,,0,0,0,,“Love is patient and kind.”
Dialogue: 0,0:18:09.82,0:18:12.57,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s not jealous.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:17.99,0:18:19.99,Default,,0,0,0,,It doesn’t become provoked,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:19.99,0:18:22.96,Default,,0,0,0,,even when things become difficult.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:25.92,0:18:27.92,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what are we going to do?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:31.71,0:18:33.76,Default,,0,0,0,,I just thought if—
Dialogue: 0,0:18:36.93,0:18:38.97,Default,,0,0,0,,No,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:40.31,0:18:42.31,Default,,0,0,0,,I’m sorry, Haley.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:47.06,0:18:49.07,Default,,0,0,0,,I’m sorry.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:50.02,0:18:52.40,Default,,0,0,0,,I shouldn’t have judged you so harshly.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:54.45,0:18:56.61,Default,,0,0,0,,I shouldn’t have judged you at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:01.04,0:19:06.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And I’m sorry for dragging you into this\Nby twisting what you said.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:07.42,0:19:11.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s OK; things happen.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:11.00,0:19:13.01,Default,,0,0,0,,I’ve been on both ends.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:20.47,0:19:24.93,Default,,0,0,0,,I should never have spoken\Nthat way to you, Celia
Dialogue: 0,0:19:26.98,0:19:31.65,Default,,0,0,0,,—I mean, to either of you.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:37.74,0:19:39.74,Default,,0,0,0,,I’ve got to get home to Nana.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:43.16,0:19:45.16,Default,,0,0,0,,I’ll call you tomorrow.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:45.79,0:19:47.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Bye.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:51.63,0:19:56.38,Default,,0,0,0,,The older sister apologized,\Neven though she was not in the wrong.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:56.38,0:20:01.10,Default,,0,0,0,,She also urged\Nthe two younger sisters to make peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:01.10,0:20:05.73,Default,,0,0,0,,It takes courage, humility,\Nand determination to apologize.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:06.77,0:20:09.23,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s interesting to note what’s stated
Dialogue: 0,0:20:09.23,0:20:13.48,Default,,0,0,0,,at Philippians 2:3:
Dialogue: 0,0:20:15.99,0:20:20.99,Default,,0,0,0,,“Do nothing out of contentiousness\Nor out of egotism,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:20.99,0:20:25.75,Default,,0,0,0,,but with humility\Nconsider others superior to you.”
Dialogue: 0,0:20:27.33,0:20:31.00,Default,,0,0,0,,That means our determined effort\Nis not to win an argument,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:31.00,0:20:33.29,Default,,0,0,0,,which could be contentious,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.29,0:20:35.51,Default,,0,0,0,,nor do we want to start a discussion
Dialogue: 0,0:20:35.51,0:20:40.09,Default,,0,0,0,,with the primary thought being\Nthat we are in the right.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:40.09,0:20:44.68,Default,,0,0,0,,That could mean\Nthat we are self-concerned, or egotistical.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:44.68,0:20:48.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Rather, in harmony\Nwith the principle of that scripture
Dialogue: 0,0:20:48.98,0:20:52.27,Default,,0,0,0,,we want to act with humility.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:52.27,0:20:55.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Our aim should be to pursue peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:55.78,0:21:00.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Even if we think the other person\Nis being unreasonable,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:00.20,0:21:02.74,Default,,0,0,0,,we apologize.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:02.74,0:21:05.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Why is it so important to do so?
Dialogue: 0,0:21:05.87,0:21:10.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Because that is what makes\Nour worship to Jehovah acceptable.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:11.17,0:21:13.84,Default,,0,0,0,,At Matthew chapter 5,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:13.84,0:21:16.63,Default,,0,0,0,,verses 23, 24,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:16.63,0:21:18.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesus makes it very clear:
Dialogue: 0,0:21:21.68,0:21:26.26,Default,,0,0,0,,“If, then, you are bringing\Nyour gift to the altar
Dialogue: 0,0:21:26.26,0:21:30.60,Default,,0,0,0,,“and there you remember\Nthat your brother has something against you,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:30.60,0:21:34.11,Default,,0,0,0,,“leave your gift there\Nin front of the altar,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:34.11,0:21:36.19,Default,,0,0,0,,“and go away.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:36.19,0:21:40.15,Default,,0,0,0,,“First make your peace with your brother,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:40.15,0:21:44.03,Default,,0,0,0,,and then come back and offer your gift.”
Dialogue: 0,0:21:45.28,0:21:49.25,Default,,0,0,0,,“One Bible scholar\Ndescribes the scene this way:
Dialogue: 0,0:21:51.25,0:21:54.29,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘The worshipper has entered the Temple;
Dialogue: 0,0:21:54.29,0:21:56.67,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘he has passed through [a] series of courts,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:56.67,0:21:58.88,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘the Court of the Gentiles,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:58.88,0:22:02.47,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘the Court of the Women,\Nthe Court of the Men.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:02.47,0:22:06.05,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Beyond that there lay\Nthe Court of the Priests
Dialogue: 0,0:22:06.05,0:22:08.97,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘into which the layman could not go.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:08.97,0:22:11.56,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘The worshipper is standing at the rail,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:11.56,0:22:15.61,Default,,0,0,0,,“ready to hand over\Nhis [living animal] to the priest.’ . . .
Dialogue: 0,0:22:15.61,0:22:18.36,Default,,0,0,0,,“At that [critical] moment,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:18.36,0:22:22.36,Default,,0,0,0,,the worshipper remembers\Nthat his brother has something against him.”
Dialogue: 0,0:22:23.74,0:22:26.12,Default,,0,0,0,,What is he to do?
Dialogue: 0,0:22:26.12,0:22:29.79,Default,,0,0,0,,“Leave your gift there\Nin front of the altar,”
Dialogue: 0,0:22:29.79,0:22:33.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesus explains, “and go away.”
Dialogue: 0,0:22:34.54,0:22:39.25,Default,,0,0,0,,What does Jesus say is more important\Nthan offering up a sacrifice?
Dialogue: 0,0:22:39.25,0:22:43.67,Default,,0,0,0,,‘First, make peace with your brother.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:43.67,0:22:47.09,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Then when you have come back,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:47.09,0:22:49.56,Default,,0,0,0,,offer up your gift.’
Dialogue: 0,0:22:49.56,0:22:52.39,Default,,0,0,0,,The expression rendered “make your peace”
Dialogue: 0,0:22:52.39,0:22:55.52,Default,,0,0,0,,means “to reconcile.”
Dialogue: 0,0:22:55.52,0:22:59.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesus’ words teach a crucial lesson:
Dialogue: 0,0:22:59.11,0:23:01.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Reconciliation, or peace,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:01.32,0:23:04.65,Default,,0,0,0,,comes before sacrifice.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:04.65,0:23:07.45,Default,,0,0,0,,The way we treat fellow worshippers
Dialogue: 0,0:23:07.45,0:23:10.91,Default,,0,0,0,,has a direct bearing\Non our relationship with God.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:12.50,0:23:15.58,Default,,0,0,0,,First John 4:20 pointedly says:
Dialogue: 0,0:23:15.58,0:23:19.92,Default,,0,0,0,,“For the one who does not love his brother,\Nwhom he has seen,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:19.92,0:23:23.13,Default,,0,0,0,,cannot love God,\Nwhom he has not seen.”
Dialogue: 0,0:23:24.51,0:23:29.01,Default,,0,0,0,,If we find ourselves in a situation\Nwhere we have offended a fellow worshipper,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:29.01,0:23:31.39,Default,,0,0,0,,we want to apply Jesus’ counsel.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:31.39,0:23:34.14,Default,,0,0,0,,We want to take the initiative
Dialogue: 0,0:23:34.14,0:23:36.77,Default,,0,0,0,,to approach our brother or sister.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:36.77,0:23:39.77,Default,,0,0,0,,We may need\Nto acknowledge their hurt feelings.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:39.77,0:23:44.32,Default,,0,0,0,,We may also need to ask,\N“What can I do to make amends?”
Dialogue: 0,0:23:44.32,0:23:48.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Often a sincere apology\Nis all that is needed.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:49.74,0:23:54.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Although our worship today\Nno longer includes animal sacrifices,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:54.41,0:23:56.41,Default,,0,0,0,,what Jesus was teaching
Dialogue: 0,0:23:56.41,0:23:59.50,Default,,0,0,0,,emphasizes that there is a connection
Dialogue: 0,0:23:59.50,0:24:02.59,Default,,0,0,0,,between peace with our brother
Dialogue: 0,0:24:02.59,0:24:05.88,Default,,0,0,0,,and acceptable worship to God.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:05.88,0:24:08.26,Default,,0,0,0,,When two humans are at odds,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:08.26,0:24:11.14,Default,,0,0,0,,there may be a measure\Nof blame on both sides,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:11.14,0:24:14.89,Default,,0,0,0,,since both are imperfect and prone to error.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:14.89,0:24:18.85,Default,,0,0,0,,This usually calls for mutual concessions.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:18.85,0:24:22.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Even if only the one apologizing is right,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:22.82,0:24:26.53,Default,,0,0,0,,the issue is not so much\Nwho is right and who is wrong
Dialogue: 0,0:24:26.53,0:24:30.07,Default,,0,0,0,,but who will take the initiative\Nto make peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:31.82,0:24:35.08,Default,,0,0,0,,When the apostle Paul heard\Nthat the Christians in Corinth
Dialogue: 0,0:24:35.08,0:24:37.79,Default,,0,0,0,,were taking fellow servants of God
Dialogue: 0,0:24:37.79,0:24:40.54,Default,,0,0,0,,to secular courts over personal differences,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:40.54,0:24:42.79,Default,,0,0,0,,he said:
Dialogue: 0,0:24:42.79,0:24:45.96,Default,,0,0,0,,“Why [do you] not\Nrather let [yourself] be wronged?
Dialogue: 0,0:24:45.96,0:24:49.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Why do you not\Nrather let [yourself] be defrauded?”
Dialogue: 0,0:24:50.84,0:24:52.93,Default,,0,0,0,,The principle is clear.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:52.93,0:24:57.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Peace among fellow believers\Nis more important than proving
Dialogue: 0,0:24:57.14,0:24:59.69,Default,,0,0,0,,who is right and who is wrong.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:01.23,0:25:04.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Keeping this in mind makes it easier\Nto apologize for a wrong
Dialogue: 0,0:25:04.77,0:25:08.28,Default,,0,0,0,,that someone thinks\Nwe’ve committed against him or her.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:08.28,0:25:11.28,Default,,0,0,0,,A heartfelt apology can open the way
Dialogue: 0,0:25:11.28,0:25:13.78,Default,,0,0,0,,to a constructive conversation.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:13.78,0:25:16.20,Default,,0,0,0,,It can minimize problems
Dialogue: 0,0:25:16.20,0:25:18.45,Default,,0,0,0,,and restore peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:20.25,0:25:22.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Brother Leonard Myers,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:22.25,0:25:24.50,Default,,0,0,0,,a helper to the Writing Committee,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:24.50,0:25:28.17,Default,,0,0,0,,will now present\Nthe next talk of this symposium,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:28.17,0:25:30.22,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Seek Peace and Pursue It’ . . .
Dialogue: 0,0:25:30.22,0:25:32.47,Default,,0,0,0,,By Forgiving Freely.”
Dialogue: 0,0:25:40.31,0:25:43.44,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s a simple fact\Nthat to be at peace with others,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:43.44,0:25:46.69,Default,,0,0,0,,we must be willing to forgive.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:46.69,0:25:49.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Please notice two examples:
Dialogue: 0,0:25:49.19,0:25:52.36,Default,,0,0,0,,A father and his teenage daughter\Ndidn’t get along.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:52.36,0:25:56.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Minor disagreements often developed\Ninto shouting matches.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:56.45,0:25:58.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally, the tension got so bad
Dialogue: 0,0:25:58.91,0:26:01.37,Default,,0,0,0,,that the daughter was asked\Nto leave the house.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:02.67,0:26:05.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Eventually, she recognized\Nthat she was at fault
Dialogue: 0,0:26:05.38,0:26:08.63,Default,,0,0,0,,and asked for her father’s forgiveness.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:08.63,0:26:11.09,Default,,0,0,0,,But instead of overlooking her mistakes,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:11.09,0:26:13.80,Default,,0,0,0,,her father rejected her efforts.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:13.80,0:26:17.64,Default,,0,0,0,,He was unwilling to extend forgiveness\Nto his own daughter.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:19.14,0:26:22.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, let’s contrast that\Nwith another example.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:22.44,0:26:26.61,Default,,0,0,0,,A blameless man was condemned to die\Nfor a crime he didn’t commit.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:27.69,0:26:31.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Shortly before he died,\Nthe innocent man stated:
Dialogue: 0,0:26:31.61,0:26:33.74,Default,,0,0,0,,“Father, forgive them,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:33.74,0:26:37.12,Default,,0,0,0,,for they do not know what they are doing.”
Dialogue: 0,0:26:37.12,0:26:41.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Those words of Jesus\Nare recorded at Luke 23:34,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:41.66,0:26:44.42,Default,,0,0,0,,and he may have been referring\Nto the Roman soldiers
Dialogue: 0,0:26:44.42,0:26:47.04,Default,,0,0,0,,who drove the nails into his hands and feet
Dialogue: 0,0:26:47.04,0:26:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and who didn’t know who he really was.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:50.00,0:26:52.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Or Jesus may have had in mind\Nsome in the crowd
Dialogue: 0,0:26:52.63,0:26:54.63,Default,,0,0,0,,who demanded his execution
Dialogue: 0,0:26:54.63,0:26:57.55,Default,,0,0,0,,but would later exercise faith in him.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:57.55,0:27:02.48,Default,,0,0,0,,The point is that Jesus\Nwas willing to forgive freely.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:03.98,0:27:07.65,Default,,0,0,0,,How do we measure up\Nwith regard to forgiveness?
Dialogue: 0,0:27:07.65,0:27:11.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Are we like Jesus,\Nwilling to forgive others freely?
Dialogue: 0,0:27:11.86,0:27:16.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Or at times, do we tend to be more\Nlike the man who was unwilling to forgive?
Dialogue: 0,0:27:18.74,0:27:21.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Granting forgiveness isn’t always easy.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:21.33,0:27:24.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Imperfection exerts\Na powerful influence over us,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:24.62,0:27:27.54,Default,,0,0,0,,sometimes robbing us of compassion.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:27.54,0:27:29.54,Default,,0,0,0,,When someone hurts us,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:29.54,0:27:33.26,Default,,0,0,0,,we may become resentful, or hold a grudge.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:33.26,0:27:37.09,Default,,0,0,0,,And perhaps some of us\Nwere taught not to forgive others.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:38.30,0:27:41.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Little wonder that cultivating\Na peaceful, forgiving spirit
Dialogue: 0,0:27:41.97,0:27:43.97,Default,,0,0,0,,can be difficult.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:43.97,0:27:48.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Still, the Bible encourages us\Nto forgive freely.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:50.36,0:27:54.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s consider another example\Nof forgiveness in the man Job.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:54.57,0:27:56.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, we’re familiar with his trials:
Dialogue: 0,0:27:56.61,0:27:59.11,Default,,0,0,0,,loss of his possessions and ten children,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:59.11,0:28:03.20,Default,,0,0,0,,a loathsome disease,\Nand his wife told him to curse God and die.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:04.29,0:28:07.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Three companions heard\Nabout Job’s calamities,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:07.00,0:28:09.79,Default,,0,0,0,,and they agreed to go comfort him.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:09.79,0:28:13.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Job 2:13 states that when they arrived,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:13.25,0:28:16.55,Default,,0,0,0,,“they sat . . . with him\Nfor seven days and seven nights,”
Dialogue: 0,0:28:16.55,0:28:19.05,Default,,0,0,0,,but they didn’t say “a word to him.”
Dialogue: 0,0:28:19.05,0:28:21.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, maybe that was a good thing
Dialogue: 0,0:28:21.05,0:28:23.26,Default,,0,0,0,,because when they finally opened\Ntheir mouths,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:23.26,0:28:27.27,Default,,0,0,0,,they deeply hurt Job\Nwith their baseless accusations.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:28.48,0:28:30.85,Default,,0,0,0,,But notice something interesting\Nabout this account.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:30.85,0:28:33.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Please turn with me to Job chapter 42.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:34.78,0:28:37.36,Default,,0,0,0,,At the end of Job’s trials, Jehovah asked Job
Dialogue: 0,0:28:37.36,0:28:40.74,Default,,0,0,0,,to do something\Nregarding these false accusers.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:40.74,0:28:45.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Notice Jehovah’s words there at Job 42,\Nth{\i1}{\fs16}{\fnArial}e {\r}B  portion of verse 8:
Dialogue: 0,0:28:47.45,0:28:51.00,Default,,0,0,0,,“And my servant Job will pray for you.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:51.00,0:28:53.13,Default,,0,0,0,,“I will surely accept his request
Dialogue: 0,0:28:53.13,0:28:57.46,Default,,0,0,0,,not to deal with you\Naccording to your foolishness.”
Dialogue: 0,0:28:57.46,0:29:01.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Did you notice\Nthat after all the false accusations,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:01.30,0:29:05.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah asked Job to pray\Nfor the men who had tormented him?
Dialogue: 0,0:29:05.81,0:29:08.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, would Job tell Jehovah,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:08.27,0:29:13.02,Default,,0,0,0,,“Jehovah, after what they said to me,\NI’m not going to forgive them”?
Dialogue: 0,0:29:13.02,0:29:15.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Would Job be resentful?
Dialogue: 0,0:29:15.86,0:29:18.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Notice the latter portion of verse 9:
Dialogue: 0,0:29:19.95,0:29:24.07,Default,,0,0,0,,“And Jehovah accepted Job’s prayer.”
Dialogue: 0,0:29:24.07,0:29:27.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Job followed Jehovah’s instructions.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:27.29,0:29:32.17,Default,,0,0,0,,What was the result\Nof Job’s integrity and his forgiving spirit?
Dialogue: 0,0:29:32.17,0:29:34.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Verse 10:
Dialogue: 0,0:29:34.21,0:29:37.55,Default,,0,0,0,,“After Job had prayed for his companions,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:37.55,0:29:41.55,Default,,0,0,0,,“Jehovah removed Job’s tribulation\Nand restored his prosperity.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:41.55,0:29:45.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah gave him double what he had before.”
Dialogue: 0,0:29:45.43,0:29:48.72,Default,,0,0,0,,The account goes on to say\Nthat Job had ten more children.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:48.72,0:29:51.31,Default,,0,0,0,,He lived for 140 more years,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:51.31,0:29:53.94,Default,,0,0,0,,and verse 17 states:
Dialogue: 0,0:29:53.94,0:29:58.86,Default,,0,0,0,,“Finally Job died,\Nafter a long and satisfying life.”
Dialogue: 0,0:29:58.86,0:30:01.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Job was blessed for his forgiving spirit,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:01.61,0:30:05.41,Default,,0,0,0,,and he set a good example for us\Nto forgive freely.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:07.03,0:30:10.00,Default,,0,0,0,,In the following dramatization\Nwith Celia and Haley,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:10.00,0:30:13.96,Default,,0,0,0,,notice why Haley finally decides\Nto forgive freely.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:39.94,0:30:41.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey, it’s me.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:41.99,0:30:43.70,Default,,0,0,0,,I’ve been thinking of you.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:44.70,0:30:46.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Great broadcast.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:46.41,0:30:48.95,Default,,0,0,0,,How did you like the new original song?
Dialogue: 0,0:30:48.95,0:30:50.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Give us a call.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:11.14,0:31:12.89,Default,,0,0,0,,I wish she’d give it a rest.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:12.89,0:31:13.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Sorry?
Dialogue: 0,0:31:13.77,0:31:15.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, nothing.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:17.02,0:31:20.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Sorry, it’s just Emily\Nfor the millionth time.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:20.65,0:31:22.69,Default,,0,0,0,,What’s the problem, love?
Dialogue: 0,0:31:22.69,0:31:25.36,Default,,0,0,0,,There’s no problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:25.36,0:31:26.99,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s just . . .
Dialogue: 0,0:31:30.28,0:31:32.33,Default,,0,0,0,,. . . difficult to let her back in?
Dialogue: 0,0:31:47.01,0:31:48.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Not that simple?
Dialogue: 0,0:31:49.85,0:31:51.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Not that simple.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:53.39,0:31:54.98,Default,,0,0,0,,You want to forgive . . .
Dialogue: 0,0:31:56.35,0:31:59.10,Default,,0,0,0,,. . . but not get burned again.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:02.52,0:32:05.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Keep in mind
Dialogue: 0,0:32:05.07,0:32:08.78,Default,,0,0,0,,that a chance to forgive\Nis a chance to imitate Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:10.24,0:32:12.83,Default,,0,0,0,,We wouldn’t want to miss that opportunity.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:15.50,0:32:17.79,Default,,0,0,0,,I never thought about it like that.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:19.21,0:32:23.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Think back to a time\Nwhen you wanted forgiveness
Dialogue: 0,0:32:26.30,0:32:28.84,Default,,0,0,0,,—when it meant everything.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:29.97,0:32:31.97,Default,,0,0,0,,How did it feel?
Dialogue: 0,0:32:31.97,0:32:33.01,Default,,0,0,0,,. . . just like your Nana does as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:33.01,0:32:34.01,Default,,0,0,0,,She really deeply cares about you.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:34.22,0:32:36.23,Default,,0,0,0,,You feel awful
Dialogue: 0,0:32:38.19,0:32:40.48,Default,,0,0,0,,that you’ve let everyone down.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:41.48,0:32:43.52,Default,,0,0,0,,You’re very precious.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:44.40,0:32:45.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:50.57,0:32:52.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Then they forgive you,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:55.04,0:32:57.37,Default,,0,0,0,,and suddenly everything is OK.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:07.59,0:33:11.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Emily, sorry I haven’t been back to you.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:13.89,0:33:15.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Have plans for tomorrow?
Dialogue: 0,0:33:18.73,0:33:21.73,Default,,0,0,0,,What good reasoning on the part of Celia!
Dialogue: 0,0:33:21.73,0:33:25.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Did you notice the expression\Nthat really touched Haley’s heart?
Dialogue: 0,0:33:25.90,0:33:30.07,Default,,0,0,0,,“A chance to forgive\Nis a chance to imitate Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:30.07,0:33:32.49,Default,,0,0,0,,We wouldn’t want to miss that opportunity.”
Dialogue: 0,0:33:33.57,0:33:37.29,Default,,0,0,0,,So when we’ve been wronged,\Nwe don’t want to miss the opportunity
Dialogue: 0,0:33:37.29,0:33:41.33,Default,,0,0,0,,to imitate Jehovah by forgiving freely.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:41.33,0:33:45.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Please notice how this is highlighted\Nat Colossians 3:13.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:46.63,0:33:49.46,Default,,0,0,0,,When we considered Job’s example,\Nremember that Jehovah
Dialogue: 0,0:33:49.46,0:33:51.84,Default,,0,0,0,,instructed him to pray for his companions.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:51.84,0:33:55.14,Default,,0,0,0,,And that helped Job\Ndisplay a forgiving spirit.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:55.14,0:33:59.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, notice here what Jehovah\Ninstructs us to do at Colossians 3:13:
Dialogue: 0,0:34:00.77,0:34:02.98,Default,,0,0,0,,“Continue putting up with one another
Dialogue: 0,0:34:02.98,0:34:06.19,Default,,0,0,0,,“and forgiving one another freely
Dialogue: 0,0:34:06.19,0:34:10.07,Default,,0,0,0,,“even if anyone has a cause for complaint\Nagainst another.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:10.07,0:34:13.11,Default,,0,0,0,,“Just as Jehovah freely forgave you,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:13.11,0:34:16.37,Default,,0,0,0,,you must also do the same.”
Dialogue: 0,0:34:17.78,0:34:20.62,Default,,0,0,0,,The Greek verb used here for “freely forgive”
Dialogue: 0,0:34:20.62,0:34:22.75,Default,,0,0,0,,is related to a word often rendered
Dialogue: 0,0:34:22.75,0:34:26.08,Default,,0,0,0,,“undeserved kindness” or “favor.”
Dialogue: 0,0:34:26.08,0:34:28.21,Default,,0,0,0,,When used in the sense of forgiving,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:28.21,0:34:30.84,Default,,0,0,0,,this verb conveys the idea of doing so
Dialogue: 0,0:34:30.84,0:34:33.43,Default,,0,0,0,,freely, generously
Dialogue: 0,0:34:33.43,0:34:37.93,Default,,0,0,0,,—just as when you, out of generosity,\Ngive a gift to someone.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:38.89,0:34:43.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah requires that we\Nfreely forgive others in imitation of him.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:43.85,0:34:45.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Did you notice the end of the verse?
Dialogue: 0,0:34:45.85,0:34:49.19,Default,,0,0,0,,“Yo{\i1}{\fs16}{\fnArial}u mu{\r}st  also do the same.”
Dialogue: 0,0:34:50.28,0:34:54.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, if the offense is minor,\Nit’s best to overlook it.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:54.28,0:34:56.87,Default,,0,0,0,,First Corinthians 13:5 states
Dialogue: 0,0:34:56.87,0:35:00.37,Default,,0,0,0,,that love “does not keep account\Nof the injury.”
Dialogue: 0,0:35:00.37,0:35:02.75,Default,,0,0,0,,And Proverbs 19:11 tells us
Dialogue: 0,0:35:02.75,0:35:06.33,Default,,0,0,0,,that “it is beauty . . .\Nto overlook an offense.”
Dialogue: 0,0:35:07.75,0:35:11.13,Default,,0,0,0,,However, if we feel that we need to talk\Nto our brother or sister
Dialogue: 0,0:35:11.13,0:35:13.51,Default,,0,0,0,,about an offense that was committed\Nagainst us,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:13.51,0:35:16.30,Default,,0,0,0,,what’s the best way to handle that?
Dialogue: 0,0:35:16.30,0:35:20.47,Default,,0,0,0,,First, we should ask Jehovah in prayer\Nfor his guidance.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:20.47,0:35:23.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Then with the brother’s good qualities\Nin mind,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:23.60,0:35:26.90,Default,,0,0,0,,graciously tell him\Nthat we want to make peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:26.90,0:35:30.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Listen carefully and empathetically.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:30.44,0:35:35.20,Default,,0,0,0,,We shouldn’t interrupt, even if we\Ndon’t agree with everything being said.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:35.20,0:35:39.83,Default,,0,0,0,,It may be that his viewpoint is wrong,\Nbut it is his viewpoint.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:40.99,0:35:45.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Then when it’s our turn to speak,\Nwe want to be gracious.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:45.08,0:35:47.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Tell the brother\Nwhat we appreciate about him;
Dialogue: 0,0:35:47.83,0:35:51.67,Default,,0,0,0,,apologize for any part that we played\Nin the misunderstanding.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:52.75,0:35:57.09,Default,,0,0,0,,If our humble efforts result in good,\Nthank Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:57.09,0:36:00.51,Default,,0,0,0,,If they don’t,\Nkeep asking Jehovah for guidance
Dialogue: 0,0:36:00.51,0:36:03.81,Default,,0,0,0,,while we look for another opportunity\Nto make peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:05.27,0:36:07.27,Default,,0,0,0,,When we truly forgive,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:07.27,0:36:10.69,Default,,0,0,0,,we make a heartfelt decision\Nto let go of resentment.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:10.69,0:36:13.94,Default,,0,0,0,,And what peace that can bring us!
Dialogue: 0,0:36:13.94,0:36:17.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, forgiving doesn’t mean\Nthat we approve of a wrong action,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:17.61,0:36:21.49,Default,,0,0,0,,consider it unimportant,\Nor pretend it didn’t happen.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:21.49,0:36:25.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Also, if we’ve been treated unjustly\Nand have a cause for complaint,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:25.83,0:36:29.25,Default,,0,0,0,,we do what we can to pursue peace\Nand resolve the matter.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:29.25,0:36:32.71,Default,,0,0,0,,And then we confidently leave it\Nin Jehovah’s hands.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:34.42,0:36:38.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Brothers and sisters, what will you\Ntake away from this consideration?
Dialogue: 0,0:36:38.34,0:36:43.14,Default,,0,0,0,,I’m sure you’ll agree that it can be\Na challenge at times to forgive.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:43.14,0:36:45.93,Default,,0,0,0,,But rather than be like the man\Nwe spoke of earlier
Dialogue: 0,0:36:45.93,0:36:48.73,Default,,0,0,0,,who refused to forgive his own daughter,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:48.73,0:36:53.65,Default,,0,0,0,,may we follow the examples of Jehovah,\NJesus, Job, and Haley
Dialogue: 0,0:36:53.65,0:36:57.28,Default,,0,0,0,,by forgiving freely, generously.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:57.28,0:37:00.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Remember, a chance to forgive
Dialogue: 0,0:37:00.11,0:37:02.62,Default,,0,0,0,,is a chance to imitate Jehovah,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:02.62,0:37:05.87,Default,,0,0,0,,and we wouldn’t want to miss\Nthat opportunity.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:05.87,0:37:08.46,Default,,0,0,0,,May all of us pursue peace
Dialogue: 0,0:37:08.46,0:37:11.54,Default,,0,0,0,,by being willing to forgive freely.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:13.50,0:37:16.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Brother Gerrit Lösch,\Na member of the Governing Body,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:16.05,0:37:18.92,Default,,0,0,0,,will now present the final talk\Nof this symposium,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:18.92,0:37:23.93,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Seek Peace and Pursue It’ . . .\NBy Using Our Gift of Speech Wisely.”
Dialogue: 0,0:37:32.40,0:37:36.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Why is it challenging\Nto use our gift of speech wisely?
Dialogue: 0,0:37:37.78,0:37:42.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Because something powerful\Nconstantly works against us.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:42.11,0:37:44.12,Default,,0,0,0,,What is it?
Dialogue: 0,0:37:44.12,0:37:46.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Imperfection.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:46.16,0:37:48.16,Default,,0,0,0,,The tongue is powerful.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:48.16,0:37:51.83,Default,,0,0,0,,It can do much good,\Nbut because of imperfection,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:51.83,0:37:55.50,Default,,0,0,0,,it can also cause much harm.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:55.50,0:38:00.34,Default,,0,0,0,,This thought is well expressed\Nin the Bible book of Proverbs.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:00.34,0:38:04.89,Default,,0,0,0,,For example, Proverbs 12:18 says:
Dialogue: 0,0:38:04.89,0:38:09.72,Default,,0,0,0,,“Thoughtless speech\Nis like the stabs of a sword,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:09.72,0:38:14.31,Default,,0,0,0,,but the tongue of the wise is a healing.”
Dialogue: 0,0:38:14.31,0:38:17.65,Default,,0,0,0,,And Proverbs 18:21 states:
Dialogue: 0,0:38:17.65,0:38:21.78,Default,,0,0,0,,“Death and life\Nare in the power of the tongue;
Dialogue: 0,0:38:21.78,0:38:26.20,Default,,0,0,0,,those who love to use it\Nwill eat its fruitage.”
Dialogue: 0,0:38:27.74,0:38:30.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Words have power,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:30.37,0:38:33.92,Default,,0,0,0,,so we need to be careful about what we say
Dialogue: 0,0:38:33.92,0:38:36.63,Default,,0,0,0,,and how we say it.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:36.63,0:38:41.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Perhaps you can recall\Nwhen someone spoke unkindly to you
Dialogue: 0,0:38:41.34,0:38:43.80,Default,,0,0,0,,and hurt you deeply.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:43.80,0:38:46.60,Default,,0,0,0,,On the other hand, thoughtful speech
Dialogue: 0,0:38:46.60,0:38:51.22,Default,,0,0,0,,can mend an aching heart\Nand heal friendships.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:51.22,0:38:54.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Because of imperfection,\Nwe all have difficulty
Dialogue: 0,0:38:54.35,0:38:56.69,Default,,0,0,0,,controlling our tongue.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:56.69,0:39:01.40,Default,,0,0,0,,This was true\Neven of the first-century disciple James.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:02.28,0:39:06.57,Default,,0,0,0,,He humbly acknowledged the challenge\Nthat all humans face
Dialogue: 0,0:39:06.57,0:39:10.83,Default,,0,0,0,,in the third chapter of his inspired letter.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:10.83,0:39:13.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Notice how James described this
Dialogue: 0,0:39:13.46,0:39:18.29,Default,,0,0,0,,at James 3:3-6, 8:
Dialogue: 0,0:39:20.13,0:39:23.76,Default,,0,0,0,,“If we put bridles in the mouths of horses
Dialogue: 0,0:39:23.76,0:39:25.76,Default,,0,0,0,,“to make them obey us,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:25.76,0:39:29.43,Default,,0,0,0,,“we guide also the whole body.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:29.43,0:39:33.10,Default,,0,0,0,,“Look also at ships: Although they are so big
Dialogue: 0,0:39:33.10,0:39:35.73,Default,,0,0,0,,“and are driven by strong winds,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:35.73,0:39:39.48,Default,,0,0,0,,“they are steered by a very small rudder
Dialogue: 0,0:39:39.48,0:39:43.74,Default,,0,0,0,,“wherever the man at the helm\Nis inclined to go.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:43.74,0:39:47.78,Default,,0,0,0,,“So, too, the tongue\Nis a small part of the body,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:47.78,0:39:50.87,Default,,0,0,0,,“and yet it makes great brags.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:50.87,0:39:53.29,Default,,0,0,0,,“See how small a fire it takes
Dialogue: 0,0:39:53.29,0:39:56.33,Default,,0,0,0,,“to set a great forest ablaze!
Dialogue: 0,0:39:56.33,0:39:59.25,Default,,0,0,0,,“The tongue is also a fire.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:59.25,0:40:02.21,Default,,0,0,0,,“The tongue represents a world\Nof unrighteousness
Dialogue: 0,0:40:02.21,0:40:05.59,Default,,0,0,0,,“among our body members,\Nfor it defiles
Dialogue: 0,0:40:05.59,0:40:09.59,Default,,0,0,0,,“all the body\Nand sets the whole course of life on fire,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:09.59,0:40:12.85,Default,,0,0,0,,and it is set on fire by Gehenna.”
Dialogue: 0,0:40:13.85,0:40:18.31,Default,,0,0,0,,And verse 8:\N“But no human can tame the tongue.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:18.31,0:40:21.02,Default,,0,0,0,,“It is unruly and injurious,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:21.02,0:40:23.28,Default,,0,0,0,,full of deadly poison.”
Dialogue: 0,0:40:23.94,0:40:26.86,Default,,0,0,0,,In addition to inherited imperfection,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:26.86,0:40:30.70,Default,,0,0,0,,our upbringing could also be a factor.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:30.70,0:40:35.25,Default,,0,0,0,,{\i1}{\fs16}{\fnArial}The Watchtower{\r}  of September 15, 2006,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:35.25,0:40:40.13,Default,,0,0,0,,page 21, paragraph 6 states:
Dialogue: 0,0:40:40.13,0:40:43.63,Default,,0,0,0,,“In addition to human imperfection,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:43.63,0:40:48.51,Default,,0,0,0,,“family environment plays a role\Nin the misuse of the tongue.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:48.51,0:40:50.68,Default,,0,0,0,,“Some people were raised in homes
Dialogue: 0,0:40:50.68,0:40:53.72,Default,,0,0,0,,“where parents were ‘not open\Nto any agreement, . . .
Dialogue: 0,0:40:53.72,0:40:56.93,Default,,0,0,0,,without self-control, fierce.’”
Dialogue: 0,0:40:58.77,0:41:02.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Despite such challenges,\Nit is possible for each one of us
Dialogue: 0,0:41:02.56,0:41:05.57,Default,,0,0,0,,to “seek peace and pursue it.”
Dialogue: 0,0:41:07.11,0:41:09.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesus set a good example
Dialogue: 0,0:41:09.15,0:41:12.49,Default,,0,0,0,,in using the gift of speech wisely.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:12.49,0:41:17.41,Default,,0,0,0,,He used his speech to encourage\Nand comfort others.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:17.41,0:41:20.58,Default,,0,0,0,,While on earth, he applied to himself\Nthe words
Dialogue: 0,0:41:20.58,0:41:24.29,Default,,0,0,0,,found at Isaiah 61:1,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:24.29,0:41:26.50,Default,,0,0,0,,which states the following:
Dialogue: 0,0:41:28.21,0:41:31.80,Default,,0,0,0,,“The spirit of the Sovereign Lord Jehovah\Nis upon me,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:31.80,0:41:36.72,Default,,0,0,0,,“because Jehovah anointed me\Nto declare good news to the meek.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:36.72,0:41:39.89,Default,,0,0,0,,“He sent me to bind up the brokenhearted,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:39.89,0:41:42.44,Default,,0,0,0,,“to proclaim liberty to the captives
Dialogue: 0,0:41:42.44,0:41:46.40,Default,,0,0,0,,and the wide opening of the eyes\Nto the prisoners.”
Dialogue: 0,0:41:47.23,0:41:51.91,Default,,0,0,0,,As recorded at Matthew 12:20,\NMatthew applies the words
Dialogue: 0,0:41:51.91,0:41:56.74,Default,,0,0,0,,of Isaiah 42:1-3 to Jesus.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:56.74,0:41:59.62,Default,,0,0,0,,At Matthew 12:20, he stated:
Dialogue: 0,0:42:00.58,0:42:03.08,Default,,0,0,0,,“No bruised reed will he crush,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:03.08,0:42:06.54,Default,,0,0,0,,“and no smoldering wick will he extinguish,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:06.54,0:42:10.09,Default,,0,0,0,,until he brings justice with success.”
Dialogue: 0,0:42:11.38,0:42:14.89,Default,,0,0,0,,We learn an important lesson\Nfrom such verses.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:14.89,0:42:18.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesus recognized that the tongue has power
Dialogue: 0,0:42:18.52,0:42:21.94,Default,,0,0,0,,—power to harm and power to heal.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:23.19,0:42:28.19,Default,,0,0,0,,{\i1}{\fs16}{\fnArial}The Watchtower{\r}  of February 15, 2015,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:28.19,0:42:32.61,Default,,0,0,0,,page 13, and paragraph 11, thus stated
Dialogue: 0,0:42:32.61,0:42:35.95,Default,,0,0,0,,that “Jesus showed discernment
Dialogue: 0,0:42:35.95,0:42:38.41,Default,,0,0,0,,in all he said and did.”
Dialogue: 0,0:42:39.91,0:42:43.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Can we imitate Jesus more closely?
Dialogue: 0,0:42:43.46,0:42:48.42,Default,,0,0,0,,If so, what will you do\Nthe next time an opportunity arises
Dialogue: 0,0:42:48.42,0:42:51.97,Default,,0,0,0,,for you to use your gift of speech wisely?
Dialogue: 0,0:42:53.13,0:42:55.26,Default,,0,0,0,,In the following dramatization,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:55.26,0:42:59.68,Default,,0,0,0,,notice how the wise use of the tongue\Nhelps to heal.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:06.35,0:43:08.06,Default,,0,0,0,,I just need a bit of help.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:08.06,0:43:10.82,Default,,0,0,0,,What do you think I should do\Nfor my winter collection?
Dialogue: 0,0:43:10.82,0:43:14.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, I don’t know,\Nbut I love what you did with your new stuff,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:14.95,0:43:16.74,Default,,0,0,0,,especially
Dialogue: 0,0:43:18.62,0:43:20.45,Default,,0,0,0,,this set.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:20.45,0:43:22.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, thanks.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:23.29,0:43:25.87,Default,,0,0,0,,You’ve all given me so many great ideas.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:25.87,0:43:28.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah, but you make them.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:28.25,0:43:29.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:29.79,0:43:31.84,Default,,0,0,0,,OK, girls.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:33.30,0:43:35.34,Default,,0,0,0,,You love it.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:37.89,0:43:39.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, this is my song.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:39.35,0:43:41.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Mine too.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:41.35,0:43:44.23,Default,,0,0,0,,“You have a treasured place
Dialogue: 0,0:43:44.23,0:43:46.52,Default,,0,0,0,,“in Jehovah’s house;
Dialogue: 0,0:43:46.52,0:43:49.86,Default,,0,0,0,,“He’ll help you out [out].
Dialogue: 0,0:43:49.86,0:43:50.73,Default,,0,0,0,,And you have . . .”
Dialogue: 0,0:43:50.73,0:43:52.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, I sing like a crow.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:52.69,0:43:54.69,Default,,0,0,0,,No, stop!
Dialogue: 0,0:43:55.53,0:43:59.95,Default,,0,0,0,,I’ll tell you who else thinks it’s her song,\Nbut you’d better have earplugs handy
Dialogue: 0,0:44:01.20,0:44:02.91,Default,,0,0,0,,—Veronica.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:02.91,0:44:05.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, my goodness!\NShe’s in love with her own voice.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:06.79,0:44:08.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Ever sit near her at the hall?
Dialogue: 0,0:44:08.71,0:44:11.42,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s like she’s the only one that can sing.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:11.42,0:44:12.25,Default,,0,0,0,,And she’s such a diva.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:12.63,0:44:17.47,Default,,0,0,0,,My first thought:\N‘Oh, no! Here we go again!
Dialogue: 0,0:44:17.47,0:44:20.14,Default,,0,0,0,,I’ve seen this movie before.’
Dialogue: 0,0:44:20.14,0:44:22.43,Default,,0,0,0,,You don’t think she’s showing off?
Dialogue: 0,0:44:22.43,0:44:24.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Is this just about Haley?
Dialogue: 0,0:44:26.14,0:44:28.44,Default,,0,0,0,,It seems it’s all about Haley.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:28.44,0:44:31.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Is there just a little bit of envy in there?
Dialogue: 0,0:44:35.24,0:44:37.32,Default,,0,0,0,,I’ve lived it.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:39.28,0:44:43.83,Default,,0,0,0,,If it’s a case of her being more careful\Nhow she comes across,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:43.83,0:44:45.87,Default,,0,0,0,,that’s another matter.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:45.87,0:44:48.29,Default,,0,0,0,,What did she suggest?
Dialogue: 0,0:44:48.29,0:44:51.25,Default,,0,0,0,,That I should tell her\Nthat she needs to stop.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:51.25,0:44:53.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Can you believe that?
Dialogue: 0,0:44:53.25,0:44:56.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Especially as a pioneer,\Nwhat kind of example is she setting?
Dialogue: 0,0:44:56.88,0:44:59.59,Default,,0,0,0,,How quickly it snowballs out of control!
Dialogue: 0,0:44:59.59,0:45:00.80,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s not what I am saying at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:00.80,0:45:02.26,Default,,0,0,0,,You are such . . .
Dialogue: 0,0:45:02.26,0:45:05.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Wow! I can’t believe you.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:05.10,0:45:08.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you that lonely\Nthat you’ve got nothing better to do?
Dialogue: 0,0:45:11.23,0:45:12.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Haley!
Dialogue: 0,0:45:16.44,0:45:19.95,Default,,0,0,0,,How difficult it can be to unravel!
Dialogue: 0,0:45:21.28,0:45:23.32,Default,,0,0,0,,I’m sorry.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:24.03,0:45:26.33,Default,,0,0,0,,I shouldn’t have judged you so harshly.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:28.29,0:45:30.33,Default,,0,0,0,,I shouldn’t have judged you at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:31.58,0:45:35.13,Default,,0,0,0,,A chance to forgive\Nis a chance to imitate Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:36.00,0:45:39.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Think back to a time\Nwhen you wanted forgiveness.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:47.31,0:45:51.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Has anyone ever tried talking to her\Nabout her singing?
Dialogue: 0,0:45:55.27,0:45:57.78,Default,,0,0,0,,You know what I love about Veronica?
Dialogue: 0,0:45:57.78,0:46:01.20,Default,,0,0,0,,She’s probably the most hospitable person\NI know.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:01.20,0:46:03.36,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s always open house at her place.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:03.36,0:46:05.66,Default,,0,0,0,,And can she cook!
Dialogue: 0,0:46:05.66,0:46:06.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Have you tried her curry?
Dialogue: 0,0:46:06.78,0:46:07.74,Default,,0,0,0,,I haven’t tried it yet.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:07.74,0:46:09.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah, it’s so good.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:09.08,0:46:10.46,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s so good.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:10.46,0:46:12.58,Default,,0,0,0,,I really look forward to that.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:12.58,0:46:13.54,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s really good.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:13.54,0:46:14.79,Default,,0,0,0,,OK, I’ll ask her.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:16.04,0:46:17.50,Default,,0,0,0,,She does these curry nights.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:17.50,0:46:18.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, you’re going to love it.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:21.30,0:46:23.47,Default,,0,0,0,,We should use our gift of speech
Dialogue: 0,0:46:23.47,0:46:26.89,Default,,0,0,0,,to honor God and to benefit others.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:26.89,0:46:30.35,Default,,0,0,0,,And if somebody gets angry at us,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:30.35,0:46:34.52,Default,,0,0,0,,our mild reply can diffuse the situation.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:34.52,0:46:37.02,Default,,0,0,0,,As Proverbs 15:1 says:
Dialogue: 0,0:46:37.02,0:46:40.03,Default,,0,0,0,,“A mild answer turns away rage,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:40.03,0:46:44.16,Default,,0,0,0,,but a harsh word stirs up anger.”
Dialogue: 0,0:46:44.16,0:46:46.66,Default,,0,0,0,,We can also use our gift of speech
Dialogue: 0,0:46:46.66,0:46:49.54,Default,,0,0,0,,to console and encourage others.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:50.58,0:46:55.58,Default,,0,0,0,,First Thessalonians 5:11, 14 states:
Dialogue: 0,0:46:56.58,0:47:01.59,Default,,0,0,0,,“Therefore, keep encouraging one another\Nand building one another up,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:01.59,0:47:05.05,Default,,0,0,0,,“just as you are in fact doing. . . .
Dialogue: 0,0:47:05.05,0:47:08.14,Default,,0,0,0,,“On the other hand, we urge you, brothers,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:08.14,0:47:11.64,Default,,0,0,0,,“to warn the disorderly, speak consolingly
Dialogue: 0,0:47:11.64,0:47:13.64,Default,,0,0,0,,“to those who are depressed,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:13.64,0:47:17.48,Default,,0,0,0,,support the weak, be patient toward all.”
Dialogue: 0,0:47:18.40,0:47:21.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, even faithful servants of Jehovah
Dialogue: 0,0:47:21.03,0:47:24.36,Default,,0,0,0,,may at times struggle with depression.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:24.36,0:47:27.45,Default,,0,0,0,,How can we help such ones?
Dialogue: 0,0:47:27.45,0:47:30.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Offer specific, genuine commendation
Dialogue: 0,0:47:30.95,0:47:35.62,Default,,0,0,0,,to help them see their own value\Nin Jehovah’s eyes.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:35.62,0:47:39.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Share with them the powerful words\Nof Bible texts
Dialogue: 0,0:47:39.34,0:47:42.84,Default,,0,0,0,,showing that Jehovah\Ntruly cares about and loves those
Dialogue: 0,0:47:42.84,0:47:46.55,Default,,0,0,0,,who “are broken at heart”\Nand “crushed in spirit.”
Dialogue: 0,0:47:47.72,0:47:50.30,Default,,0,0,0,,We can also use the power of our tongue
Dialogue: 0,0:47:50.30,0:47:53.93,Default,,0,0,0,,to provide much needed encouragement\Nto others.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:55.35,0:47:59.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Has a fellow believer lost\Na loved one in death?
Dialogue: 0,0:47:59.52,0:48:03.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Sympathetic words\Nexpressing our care and concern
Dialogue: 0,0:48:03.65,0:48:07.32,Default,,0,0,0,,can comfort a grieving heart.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:07.32,0:48:11.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Is an elderly brother or sister\Nfeeling unneeded?
Dialogue: 0,0:48:11.62,0:48:15.12,Default,,0,0,0,,A thoughtful tongue can reassure older ones
Dialogue: 0,0:48:15.12,0:48:18.37,Default,,0,0,0,,that they are valued and appreciated.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:19.42,0:48:23.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Is someone struggling with a chronic illness?
Dialogue: 0,0:48:23.13,0:48:26.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Kind words shared on the phone or in person
Dialogue: 0,0:48:26.80,0:48:31.26,Default,,0,0,0,,can do much to lift the spirits\Nof one who is sick.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:32.76,0:48:34.85,Default,,0,0,0,,How pleased our Creator must be
Dialogue: 0,0:48:34.85,0:48:38.44,Default,,0,0,0,,when we use the power of speech\Nto utter sayings
Dialogue: 0,0:48:38.44,0:48:40.86,Default,,0,0,0,,that are “good for building up”!
Dialogue: 0,0:48:42.19,0:48:45.15,Default,,0,0,0,,We may not be able to fix their problems,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:45.15,0:48:48.03,Default,,0,0,0,,but we can let them know that we love them
Dialogue: 0,0:48:48.03,0:48:50.28,Default,,0,0,0,,and we care about them.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:51.32,0:48:56.33,Default,,0,0,0,,For example, you can arrange\Nto spend time with him or her.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:56.33,0:48:58.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Additionally, we can use God’s Word
Dialogue: 0,0:48:58.92,0:49:01.63,Default,,0,0,0,,to strengthen them.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:01.63,0:49:04.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Or you may notice\Nthat someone in the congregation
Dialogue: 0,0:49:04.67,0:49:07.34,Default,,0,0,0,,is discouraged or depressed.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:07.34,0:49:09.97,Default,,0,0,0,,You could read an encouraging Bible verse
Dialogue: 0,0:49:09.97,0:49:13.05,Default,,0,0,0,,and even offer to say a prayer.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:13.05,0:49:15.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Reassure such ones
Dialogue: 0,0:49:15.06,0:49:19.02,Default,,0,0,0,,that their brothers and sisters\Nin the congregation love them.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:20.10,0:49:22.23,Default,,0,0,0,,And speak in a way that shows
Dialogue: 0,0:49:22.23,0:49:25.73,Default,,0,0,0,,that you really mean and believe\Nwhat you say.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:27.40,0:49:30.07,Default,,0,0,0,,This symposium has given each one of us
Dialogue: 0,0:49:30.07,0:49:33.83,Default,,0,0,0,,much to think about, has it not?
Dialogue: 0,0:49:33.83,0:49:38.83,Default,,0,0,0,,We have been reminded\Nthat seeking peace is not always easy.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:38.83,0:49:41.96,Default,,0,0,0,,We have also learned\Nthat the pursuit of peace
Dialogue: 0,0:49:41.96,0:49:44.25,Default,,0,0,0,,requires effort.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:45.67,0:49:48.21,Default,,0,0,0,,In what specific ways are you resolved
Dialogue: 0,0:49:48.21,0:49:51.18,Default,,0,0,0,,to “seek peace and pursue it”
Dialogue: 0,0:49:51.18,0:49:53.89,Default,,0,0,0,,in the days ahead?
Dialogue: 0,0:49:53.89,0:49:57.77,Default,,0,0,0,,May we all continue to pursue peace
Dialogue: 0,0:49:57.77,0:50:02.23,Default,,0,0,0,,(1) by not quickly taking offense,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:02.23,0:50:05.65,Default,,0,0,0,,(2) by apologizing,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:05.65,0:50:08.90,Default,,0,0,0,,(3) by forgiving freely,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:08.90,0:50:13.32,Default,,0,0,0,,and (4) by using our gift of speech wisely
Dialogue: 0,0:50:13.32,0:50:16.95,Default,,0,0,0,,to encourage and comfort others.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:16.95,0:50:19.79,Default,,0,0,0,,And may Jehovah, “the God of peace,”
Dialogue: 0,0:50:19.79,0:50:22.67,Default,,0,0,0,,bless you abundantly for doing so!
Dialogue: 0,0:50:24.50,0:50:26.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you, brothers, for reminding us
Dialogue: 0,0:50:26.96,0:50:30.46,Default,,0,0,0,,that the peace we enjoy\Ndoes not happen by chance.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:30.46,0:50:34.22,Default,,0,0,0,,It requires continuous effort on our part,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:34.22,0:50:37.97,Default,,0,0,0,,but we can succeed with Jehovah’s help.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:41.18,0:50:44.60,Default,,0,0,0,,We have now come\Nto the concluding talk of this session.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:45.94,0:50:50.94,Default,,0,0,0,,True Christians come from a variety\Nof backgrounds and cultures.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:50.94,0:50:54.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Individual consciences differ.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:54.24,0:50:56.74,Default,,0,0,0,,How can we remain united
Dialogue: 0,0:50:56.74,0:50:59.79,Default,,0,0,0,,despite these differences?
Dialogue: 0,0:50:59.79,0:51:02.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Please give your attention\Nto Brother David Splane,
Dialogue: 0,0:51:02.96,0:51:04.96,Default,,0,0,0,,a member of the Governing Body,
Dialogue: 0,0:51:04.96,0:51:07.88,Default,,0,0,0,,as he delivers the talk entitled
Dialogue: 0,0:51:07.88,0:51:12.51,Default,,0,0,0,,“Safeguard Our ‘Uniting Bond of Peace’!”
Dialogue: 0,0:51:20.31,0:51:22.31,Default,,0,0,0,,When we think of unity,
Dialogue: 0,0:51:22.31,0:51:25.85,Default,,0,0,0,,the words of Psalm 133:1 may come to mind.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:25.85,0:51:27.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s read them.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:27.10,0:51:29.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, the words\Naren’t going to be on the screen,
Dialogue: 0,0:51:29.27,0:51:31.78,Default,,0,0,0,,so let’s look them up in the Bible.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:31.78,0:51:33.28,Default,,0,0,0,,I’ll give you a moment.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:33.28,0:51:37.70,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s Psalm 133
Dialogue: 0,0:51:37.70,0:51:39.53,Default,,0,0,0,,and verse 1.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:39.53,0:51:41.95,Default,,0,0,0,,It says: “Look!
Dialogue: 0,0:51:41.95,0:51:44.75,Default,,0,0,0,,“How good and how pleasant it is
Dialogue: 0,0:51:44.75,0:51:48.83,Default,,0,0,0,,for brothers to dwell together in unity!”
Dialogue: 0,0:51:48.83,0:51:53.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we certainly agree\Nwith these words of David.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:53.67,0:51:58.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, speaking of David,\Nhe knew the value of unity.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:58.18,0:52:01.01,Default,,0,0,0,,And we may remember\Nthat he didn’t always get
Dialogue: 0,0:52:01.01,0:52:03.39,Default,,0,0,0,,to experience it in his own life.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:03.39,0:52:07.44,Default,,0,0,0,,The beginning and the end\Nof his reign were marked by civil war
Dialogue: 0,0:52:07.44,0:52:10.94,Default,,0,0,0,,—the very opposite of unity.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:10.94,0:52:13.11,Default,,0,0,0,,But you’d think it would have been easy
Dialogue: 0,0:52:13.11,0:52:15.65,Default,,0,0,0,,for the Israelites to remain united.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:15.65,0:52:18.61,Default,,0,0,0,,After all, they came from the same roots;
Dialogue: 0,0:52:18.61,0:52:21.28,Default,,0,0,0,,they were all children of Abraham;
Dialogue: 0,0:52:21.28,0:52:24.29,Default,,0,0,0,,they spoke a common language—Hebrew;
Dialogue: 0,0:52:24.29,0:52:28.50,Default,,0,0,0,,and they came\Nfrom a similar social background.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:28.50,0:52:31.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Their ancestors had all been slaves in Egypt.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:31.17,0:52:36.05,Default,,0,0,0,,So there was no basis\Nfor anybody to brag about his heritage.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:36.05,0:52:41.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Still, the Israelites\Nfound reasons to hate one another.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:41.01,0:52:43.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Israel’s first king was from Benjamin.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:43.60,0:52:46.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Its second king was from Judah.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:46.60,0:52:51.06,Default,,0,0,0,,That was reason enough\Nto start a war in Israel.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:51.06,0:52:54.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s fast-forward now to the first century.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:54.61,0:52:58.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Unity is so important\Nthat it was on Jesus’ mind
Dialogue: 0,0:52:58.40,0:53:00.66,Default,,0,0,0,,on the night before he died.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:00.66,0:53:02.91,Default,,0,0,0,,You remember that he prayed to his Father
Dialogue: 0,0:53:02.91,0:53:05.41,Default,,0,0,0,,that his disciples ‘might be one
Dialogue: 0,0:53:05.41,0:53:09.83,Default,,0,0,0,,just as he and the Father are one.’
Dialogue: 0,0:53:09.83,0:53:12.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, that could have been a challenge.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:12.92,0:53:14.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Why do we say that?
Dialogue: 0,0:53:14.92,0:53:17.05,Default,,0,0,0,,From a human standpoint,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:17.05,0:53:20.22,Default,,0,0,0,,there was no reason\Nfor Jesus’ disciples to be united.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:20.22,0:53:22.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Unlike the Israelites,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:22.22,0:53:25.39,Default,,0,0,0,,they did not have a common ancestor,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:25.39,0:53:28.14,Default,,0,0,0,,they did not have a common mother tongue,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:28.14,0:53:32.06,Default,,0,0,0,,and they came\Nfrom a variety of social backgrounds.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:32.06,0:53:37.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Think of it: The first Christians\Nwere Jews or Jewish proselytes.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:37.03,0:53:41.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Growing up, they were taught\Nthat Gentiles were unclean,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:41.03,0:53:43.74,Default,,0,0,0,,and they wouldn’t even\Nenter the home of a Gentile,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:43.74,0:53:45.74,Default,,0,0,0,,let alone preach to one.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:47.04,0:53:52.00,Default,,0,0,0,,As for Gentile Christians,\Nthey came “from every nation under heaven.”
Dialogue: 0,0:53:52.00,0:53:54.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Most of them knew nothing\Nof the Hebrew language
Dialogue: 0,0:53:54.46,0:53:56.09,Default,,0,0,0,,or the Hebrew Scriptures.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:56.09,0:53:58.59,Default,,0,0,0,,They’d worshipped false gods.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:58.59,0:54:02.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Some had been highly educated at Athens,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:02.22,0:54:05.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Alexandria, or some other\Ncenter of worldly wisdom.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:05.72,0:54:09.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Others had little formal education.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:09.39,0:54:12.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Yet, when they accepted the truth,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:12.10,0:54:15.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Christians became united\Nand at peace with one another.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:17.19,0:54:19.49,Default,,0,0,0,,The apostle Paul wanted to help them
Dialogue: 0,0:54:19.49,0:54:22.86,Default,,0,0,0,,to safeguard that bond of peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:22.86,0:54:25.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, that’s the theme\Nof our discussion this morning.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:25.99,0:54:27.99,Default,,0,0,0,,And we’re going to look at his words
Dialogue: 0,0:54:27.99,0:54:32.87,Default,,0,0,0,,recorded at Ephesians 4:3-6,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:32.87,0:54:37.38,Default,,0,0,0,,and we’re going\Nto focus in on a particular expression
Dialogue: 0,0:54:37.38,0:54:40.21,Default,,0,0,0,,in these verses.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:40.21,0:54:42.09,Default,,0,0,0,,This is Ephesians chapter 4.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:42.09,0:54:44.51,Default,,0,0,0,,I’ll give you a moment.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:44.51,0:54:46.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Ephesians chapter 4
Dialogue: 0,0:54:46.85,0:54:50.10,Default,,0,0,0,,and we’re going to read verses 3-6.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:51.56,0:54:55.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, Paul is interested in unity here,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:55.81,0:54:59.40,Default,,0,0,0,,so let’s see how he frames his discussion.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:59.40,0:55:02.86,Default,,0,0,0,,He says: “Earnestly endeavoring
Dialogue: 0,0:55:02.86,0:55:07.32,Default,,0,0,0,,“[so an effort is involved,\Nearnestly endeavoring]
Dialogue: 0,0:55:07.32,0:55:10.33,Default,,0,0,0,,“to maintain the oneness of the spirit
Dialogue: 0,0:55:10.33,0:55:14.62,Default,,0,0,0,,“in the uniting bond of peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:14.62,0:55:18.04,Default,,0,0,0,,“One body there is, and one spirit,
Dialogue: 0,0:55:18.04,0:55:21.26,Default,,0,0,0,,“just as you were called\Nto the one hope of your calling;
Dialogue: 0,0:55:21.26,0:55:25.18,Default,,0,0,0,,“[and then he emphasizes]\None Lord, one faith,
Dialogue: 0,0:55:25.18,0:55:28.30,Default,,0,0,0,,“one baptism; one God
Dialogue: 0,0:55:28.30,0:55:31.68,Default,,0,0,0,,and Father of all.”
Dialogue: 0,0:55:31.68,0:55:34.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, let’s go back to verse 3\Nand look at the expression
Dialogue: 0,0:55:34.81,0:55:38.69,Default,,0,0,0,,“the uniting bond of peace.”
Dialogue: 0,0:55:38.69,0:55:43.69,Default,,0,0,0,,So our discussion\Nis “Safeguard Our ‘Uniting Bond of Peace’!”
Dialogue: 0,0:55:43.69,0:55:47.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, the {\i1}{\fs16}{\fnArial}Study Bible{\r}\Nhas an interesting note on that expression.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:47.20,0:55:52.04,Default,,0,0,0,,It tells us that the word\Ntranslated “uniting bond”
Dialogue: 0,0:55:52.04,0:55:56.50,Default,,0,0,0,,can also be translated “ligament”\N—ligament.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:56.50,0:56:00.59,Default,,0,0,0,,And it is translated\N“ligament” in other verses.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:00.59,0:56:02.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, we know what a ligament is.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:02.88,0:56:07.18,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s a band of strong tissue\Nthat holds our bones together.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:07.18,0:56:11.60,Default,,0,0,0,,So when we talk\Nabout the uniting bond of peace,
Dialogue: 0,0:56:11.60,0:56:14.39,Default,,0,0,0,,we mean that peace is the ligament.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:14.39,0:56:18.65,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s the tissue\Nthat holds God’s people together.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:18.65,0:56:23.57,Default,,0,0,0,,That was true in the first century\Nand is true today.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:23.57,0:56:25.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Like the early Christians,
Dialogue: 0,0:56:25.57,0:56:27.95,Default,,0,0,0,,we come from different backgrounds;
Dialogue: 0,0:56:27.95,0:56:29.95,Default,,0,0,0,,we speak different languages.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:29.95,0:56:33.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Yet, Jehovah has shown us\Nhow to remain united
Dialogue: 0,0:56:33.70,0:56:36.62,Default,,0,0,0,,and at peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:36.62,0:56:40.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, let’s explain\Nwhat we mean by being united.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:40.38,0:56:44.51,Default,,0,0,0,,To be united doesn’t mean\Nthat we all have to like the same things
Dialogue: 0,0:56:44.51,0:56:47.51,Default,,0,0,0,,or we all have\Nto think the same on every subject.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:47.51,0:56:51.35,Default,,0,0,0,,There’s room\Nfor a variety of tastes and opinions.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:51.35,0:56:54.10,Default,,0,0,0,,There’s variety on this convention program.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:54.10,0:56:56.64,Default,,0,0,0,,We don’t all wear the same style of suit
Dialogue: 0,0:56:56.64,0:57:00.10,Default,,0,0,0,,or have the same color of tie.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:00.10,0:57:02.44,Default,,0,0,0,,What about you?
Dialogue: 0,0:57:02.44,0:57:05.44,Default,,0,0,0,,What’s your favorite color?
Dialogue: 0,0:57:05.44,0:57:08.20,Default,,0,0,0,,your favorite food?
Dialogue: 0,0:57:08.20,0:57:10.36,Default,,0,0,0,,your favorite pet?
Dialogue: 0,0:57:10.36,0:57:14.91,Default,,0,0,0,,In Jehovah’s organization,\Nthere are dog lovers and cat lovers.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:14.91,0:57:18.71,Default,,0,0,0,,And not everyone\Nlikes the same breed of dog or cat.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:18.71,0:57:20.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Have you ever visited someone
Dialogue: 0,0:57:20.83,0:57:24.00,Default,,0,0,0,,who has a pet\Nthat he thinks is just adorable?
Dialogue: 0,0:57:24.00,0:57:26.01,Default,,0,0,0,,You take one look at the animal,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:26.01,0:57:29.09,Default,,0,0,0,,and you wonder\Nhow anyone could love a face like that.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:29.09,0:57:30.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Yet, he does.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:30.72,0:57:35.56,Default,,0,0,0,,People are different,\Nand their pets are grateful for that.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:37.60,0:57:40.44,Default,,0,0,0,,The variety we find among God’s people today
Dialogue: 0,0:57:40.44,0:57:42.52,Default,,0,0,0,,will continue on into the new world.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:42.52,0:57:44.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah loves variety.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:44.98,0:57:47.15,Default,,0,0,0,,How many colors are there?
Dialogue: 0,0:57:47.15,0:57:51.53,Default,,0,0,0,,How many species of plants,\Nbirds, and animals are there?
Dialogue: 0,0:57:51.53,0:57:55.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Among God’s creation,\Nwe find the simple and the complex,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:55.83,0:58:00.83,Default,,0,0,0,,the plain and the fancy,\Nthe sweet and the sour,
Dialogue: 0,0:58:00.83,0:58:03.50,Default,,0,0,0,,the rough and the smooth.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:03.50,0:58:05.75,Default,,0,0,0,,There’s great variety among people.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:05.75,0:58:07.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Even in the new world,
Dialogue: 0,0:58:07.76,0:58:10.59,Default,,0,0,0,,perfect humans won’t have\Nthe same personality,
Dialogue: 0,0:58:10.59,0:58:13.26,Default,,0,0,0,,talents, and abilities.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:13.26,0:58:15.72,Default,,0,0,0,,You’ve always wanted to play the violin?
Dialogue: 0,0:58:15.72,0:58:17.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Don’t think that when you’re perfect,
Dialogue: 0,0:58:17.72,0:58:21.10,Default,,0,0,0,,you’ll just be able\Nto pick up a violin and play.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:21.10,0:58:25.19,Default,,0,0,0,,And there’s no guarantee\Nyou’ll be able to play in our orchestra.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:26.77,0:58:29.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, one way to maintain unity
Dialogue: 0,0:58:29.19,0:58:32.45,Default,,0,0,0,,is to respect the conscience of others.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:32.45,0:58:34.45,Default,,0,0,0,,This is very important
Dialogue: 0,0:58:34.45,0:58:37.41,Default,,0,0,0,,because very often when unity is disturbed,
Dialogue: 0,0:58:37.41,0:58:39.87,Default,,0,0,0,,it’s because we don’t respect
Dialogue: 0,0:58:39.87,0:58:42.21,Default,,0,0,0,,the ability of other brothers and sisters
Dialogue: 0,0:58:42.21,0:58:44.21,Default,,0,0,0,,to decide things for themselves.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:44.21,0:58:47.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, what do we mean by the conscience?
Dialogue: 0,0:58:47.46,0:58:49.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s be simple.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:49.17,0:58:51.17,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s the faculty
Dialogue: 0,0:58:51.17,0:58:55.09,Default,,0,0,0,,that helps us determine right from wrong.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:55.09,0:58:56.72,Default,,0,0,0,,I’m going to repeat that.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:56.72,0:58:59.22,Default,,0,0,0,,The conscience is the faculty
Dialogue: 0,0:58:59.22,0:59:03.48,Default,,0,0,0,,to determine right from wrong.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:03.48,0:59:07.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, let’s consider\Nhow our upbringing and our culture
Dialogue: 0,0:59:07.23,0:59:11.24,Default,,0,0,0,,can help shape\Nour personal view of right and wrong.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:12.90,0:59:15.99,Default,,0,0,0,,In some cultures, there are large families.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:15.99,0:59:18.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Conversation around the dinner table is loud.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:18.74,0:59:20.87,Default,,0,0,0,,You can hardly hear yourself think.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:20.87,0:59:23.08,Default,,0,0,0,,The children tease one another
Dialogue: 0,0:59:23.08,0:59:26.96,Default,,0,0,0,,and don’t hesitate\Nto ask each other personal questions.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:26.96,0:59:29.55,Default,,0,0,0,,The girls borrow each other’s clothes,
Dialogue: 0,0:59:29.55,0:59:32.55,Default,,0,0,0,,sometimes without asking.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:32.55,0:59:34.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Some people would say that’s wrong,
Dialogue: 0,0:59:34.68,0:59:36.68,Default,,0,0,0,,but the girls see nothing wrong with it,
Dialogue: 0,0:59:36.68,0:59:38.85,Default,,0,0,0,,and neither do their parents.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:38.85,0:59:43.35,Default,,0,0,0,,In other cultures, family members\Nare polite and courteous,
Dialogue: 0,0:59:43.35,0:59:47.65,Default,,0,0,0,,but they don’t talk much\Nabout their plans or their feelings.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:47.65,0:59:51.19,Default,,0,0,0,,The parents don’t often talk about their past
Dialogue: 0,0:59:51.19,0:59:54.65,Default,,0,0,0,,because they value their privacy.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:54.65,0:59:56.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, some who were raised that way
Dialogue: 0,0:59:56.78,1:00:00.33,Default,,0,0,0,,tend to be rather strict\Nwith themselves and others.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:00.33,1:00:04.16,Default,,0,0,0,,They have definite views of right and wrong.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:04.16,1:00:06.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Borrow their clothes without asking
Dialogue: 0,1:00:06.42,1:00:08.58,Default,,0,0,0,,and they’ll say: “That’s stealing.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:08.58,1:00:10.71,Default,,0,0,0,,I’m calling the elders.”
Dialogue: 0,1:00:10.71,1:00:14.63,Default,,0,0,0,,There are no gray areas with them.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:14.63,1:00:16.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, there are lots of exceptions,
Dialogue: 0,1:00:16.63,1:00:19.93,Default,,0,0,0,,and we’re not saying that everyone\Nin a certain culture fits the bill.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:19.93,1:00:22.31,Default,,0,0,0,,But you get the idea.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:22.31,1:00:24.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, what do you suppose happens
Dialogue: 0,1:00:24.98,1:00:26.98,Default,,0,0,0,,when a publisher from one culture
Dialogue: 0,1:00:26.98,1:00:31.40,Default,,0,0,0,,moves into a congregation\Nwhere the other culture predominates?
Dialogue: 0,1:00:31.40,1:00:33.98,Default,,0,0,0,,If he doesn’t adjust\Nhis way of viewing others,
Dialogue: 0,1:00:33.98,1:00:35.99,Default,,0,0,0,,he’ll be miserable.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:35.99,1:00:38.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Is one way right and the other wrong?
Dialogue: 0,1:00:38.03,1:00:39.66,Default,,0,0,0,,No.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:39.66,1:00:44.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Members of both cultures\Ncould learn from one another.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:44.37,1:00:47.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Speaking of culture, we might ask ourselves,
Dialogue: 0,1:00:47.21,1:00:49.42,Default,,0,0,0,,‘How do I feel about brothers and sisters
Dialogue: 0,1:00:49.42,1:00:53.09,Default,,0,0,0,,who come from cultures\Nthat are very different from my own?’
Dialogue: 0,1:00:53.09,1:00:55.42,Default,,0,0,0,,They may speak with an accent.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:55.42,1:00:58.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Their style of dress may be different.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:58.63,1:01:02.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Their manners and food\Nmay not be what we’re used to.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:02.93,1:01:05.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Suppose that an elder\Nis younger than we are
Dialogue: 0,1:01:05.60,1:01:07.89,Default,,0,0,0,,or from a different race.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:07.89,1:01:10.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Will we accept his counsel?
Dialogue: 0,1:01:10.35,1:01:13.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Will we ask him for counsel?
Dialogue: 0,1:01:13.48,1:01:16.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Or will we look for an elder who’s older
Dialogue: 0,1:01:16.49,1:01:19.11,Default,,0,0,0,,and from a similar background?
Dialogue: 0,1:01:19.11,1:01:21.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Will we celebrate our differences,
Dialogue: 0,1:01:21.49,1:01:26.08,Default,,0,0,0,,or will we allow them to disturb our unity?
Dialogue: 0,1:01:26.08,1:01:28.08,Default,,0,0,0,,So that’s one thing.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:28.08,1:01:30.92,Default,,0,0,0,,But let’s talk about our personal history.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:30.92,1:01:35.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Our personal history\Ncan also affect our view of right and wrong.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:35.67,1:01:40.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Some grew up in a household\Nwhere alcohol was a problem.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:40.68,1:01:43.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Home was not a happy place.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:43.51,1:01:48.52,Default,,0,0,0,,And as adults, they stay\Nas far away from alcohol as they can,
Dialogue: 0,1:01:48.52,1:01:52.06,Default,,0,0,0,,and they take a dim view\Nof anyone who uses it,
Dialogue: 0,1:01:52.06,1:01:54.11,Default,,0,0,0,,even in moderation.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:54.11,1:01:58.99,Default,,0,0,0,,To them, it’s just plain wrong to drink.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:58.99,1:02:01.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Others have only good memories\Nof their childhood home.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:01.95,1:02:04.95,Default,,0,0,0,,At supper time,\Nthere was always wine on the table,
Dialogue: 0,1:02:04.95,1:02:07.08,Default,,0,0,0,,but nobody ever abused it.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:09.00,1:02:12.00,Default,,0,0,0,,A person who left behind an immoral lifestyle
Dialogue: 0,1:02:12.00,1:02:15.84,Default,,0,0,0,,might be extremely sensitive\Nabout choices of clothing.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:15.84,1:02:18.09,Default,,0,0,0,,He may be troubled by a clothing style
Dialogue: 0,1:02:18.09,1:02:22.13,Default,,0,0,0,,that other brothers and sisters\Nfind totally acceptable.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:22.13,1:02:24.14,Default,,0,0,0,,If they’re not careful,
Dialogue: 0,1:02:24.14,1:02:26.43,Default,,0,0,0,,those who tend to be strict with themselves
Dialogue: 0,1:02:26.43,1:02:28.97,Default,,0,0,0,,could impose their conscience on others.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:28.97,1:02:33.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let’s consider a familiar scenario.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:33.23,1:02:37.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Four publishers\Nare working rural territory in a car group.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:37.36,1:02:40.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, each home is separated from the next
Dialogue: 0,1:02:40.24,1:02:42.74,Default,,0,0,0,,by many miles or kilometers.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:42.74,1:02:44.95,Default,,0,0,0,,At the first call, the driver
Dialogue: 0,1:02:44.95,1:02:47.95,Default,,0,0,0,,and her companion get out\Nand the other sisters stay in the car.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:47.95,1:02:50.70,Default,,0,0,0,,They have no choice.\NThere’s no place to go.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:50.70,1:02:53.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, the householder has many questions,
Dialogue: 0,1:02:53.33,1:02:56.04,Default,,0,0,0,,and a Bible study has started.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:56.04,1:02:59.84,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s noon when the two publishers\Nreturn to the car
Dialogue: 0,1:02:59.84,1:03:02.09,Default,,0,0,0,,—all smiles.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:02.09,1:03:04.26,Default,,0,0,0,,You know what’s coming next, don’t you?
Dialogue: 0,1:03:05.72,1:03:08.43,Default,,0,0,0,,One of the sisters in the back seat says,
Dialogue: 0,1:03:08.43,1:03:12.73,Default,,0,0,0,,“Well, the two of us\Ncan’t count any time this morning.”
Dialogue: 0,1:03:12.73,1:03:14.44,Default,,0,0,0,,What’s she done?
Dialogue: 0,1:03:14.44,1:03:17.73,Default,,0,0,0,,She’s spoken for herself\Nand for her companion.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:17.73,1:03:22.74,Default,,0,0,0,,And unintentionally, she’s imposed\Nher own conscience on her friend.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:22.74,1:03:25.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, if she doesn’t want\Nto count any time, that’s her business.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:25.91,1:03:29.70,Default,,0,0,0,,It would be best\Nif she kept her business to herself.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:30.83,1:03:34.92,Default,,0,0,0,,If you’ve ever visited a foreign country\Nand gone on a guided tour,
Dialogue: 0,1:03:34.92,1:03:37.92,Default,,0,0,0,,probably one of the things\Nthe tour guide wanted to show you
Dialogue: 0,1:03:37.92,1:03:40.92,Default,,0,0,0,,was the architecture inside a church.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:40.92,1:03:43.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, some brothers\Nhave no problem entering a church
Dialogue: 0,1:03:43.51,1:03:48.10,Default,,0,0,0,,if it’s part of a tour because to them\Nit’s no different from visiting a museum.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:48.10,1:03:51.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Others who were\Nstrong supporters of false religion
Dialogue: 0,1:03:51.68,1:03:54.39,Default,,0,0,0,,couldn’t enter a church for any reason,
Dialogue: 0,1:03:54.39,1:03:57.31,Default,,0,0,0,,not even to attend a wedding or a funeral.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:57.31,1:04:01.82,Default,,0,0,0,,To them, it’s just plain wrong.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:01.82,1:04:04.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Consciences can differ in this respect,
Dialogue: 0,1:04:04.40,1:04:07.03,Default,,0,0,0,,and we have to respect that;\Nwe have to acknowledge that.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:07.03,1:04:10.95,Default,,0,0,0,,And we’re going to expand\Non that idea in a moment.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:10.95,1:04:14.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we’ve hardly scratched the surface
Dialogue: 0,1:04:14.04,1:04:16.96,Default,,0,0,0,,when it comes to describing\Nthe variety of personalities
Dialogue: 0,1:04:16.96,1:04:20.21,Default,,0,0,0,,and viewpoints in Jehovah’s organization.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:20.21,1:04:22.50,Default,,0,0,0,,So here’s the question:
Dialogue: 0,1:04:22.50,1:04:26.17,Default,,0,0,0,,How can we maintain our unity?
Dialogue: 0,1:04:26.17,1:04:27.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Remember what Paul said?
Dialogue: 0,1:04:27.84,1:04:31.85,Default,,0,0,0,,“Earnestly endeavoring to maintain”
Dialogue: 0,1:04:31.85,1:04:36.06,Default,,0,0,0,,—maintain this perfect bond of unity.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:36.06,1:04:39.81,Default,,0,0,0,,It means that we have to put forth effort
Dialogue: 0,1:04:39.81,1:04:42.11,Default,,0,0,0,,to maintain that unity.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:42.11,1:04:46.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, first of all,\Nit’ll help a lot to get well-acquainted
Dialogue: 0,1:04:46.03,1:04:48.86,Default,,0,0,0,,with brothers and sisters\Nwho think differently from us.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:48.86,1:04:50.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Get to know their background.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:50.87,1:04:53.62,Default,,0,0,0,,That’ll help you not to overreact
Dialogue: 0,1:04:53.62,1:04:56.54,Default,,0,0,0,,when they take a position\Nthat you don’t agree with.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:56.54,1:04:59.04,Default,,0,0,0,,It’ll help us not to judge them.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:59.04,1:05:01.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, Paul wrote very plainly on that subject
Dialogue: 0,1:05:01.84,1:05:05.80,Default,,0,0,0,,in the words found at Romans 14:4
Dialogue: 0,1:05:07.72,1:05:10.22,Default,,0,0,0,,—simple statement but very powerful.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:10.22,1:05:13.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s check it out together\Nat Romans chapter 14
Dialogue: 0,1:05:13.60,1:05:15.93,Default,,0,0,0,,(I’ll give you a moment)
Dialogue: 0,1:05:15.93,1:05:17.93,Default,,0,0,0,,and verse 4.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:19.81,1:05:22.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul writes: “Who are you
Dialogue: 0,1:05:22.98,1:05:26.40,Default,,0,0,0,,“to judge the servant of another?
Dialogue: 0,1:05:26.40,1:05:29.65,Default,,0,0,0,,“To his own master he stands or falls.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:29.65,1:05:32.66,Default,,0,0,0,,“Indeed, he will be made to stand,
Dialogue: 0,1:05:32.66,1:05:36.16,Default,,0,0,0,,for Jehovah can make him stand.”
Dialogue: 0,1:05:36.16,1:05:39.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let’s go back\Nand look at that first sentence again:
Dialogue: 0,1:05:39.12,1:05:42.33,Default,,0,0,0,,“Who are you to judge
Dialogue: 0,1:05:42.33,1:05:45.25,Default,,0,0,0,,the servant of another?”
Dialogue: 0,1:05:45.25,1:05:47.30,Default,,0,0,0,,We know what a judge does.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:47.30,1:05:50.68,Default,,0,0,0,,He declares someone guilty or not guilty.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:50.68,1:05:52.68,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s not our job.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:52.68,1:05:55.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah is the Judge.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:55.47,1:05:59.81,Default,,0,0,0,,If each of us concentrates\Non his own thinking and his own conscience,
Dialogue: 0,1:05:59.81,1:06:04.19,Default,,0,0,0,,the peace and unity\Nof the congregation will be preserved.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:05.57,1:06:08.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we all want to be balanced
Dialogue: 0,1:06:08.15,1:06:11.57,Default,,0,0,0,,when we determine\Nwhat is right and what is wrong.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:11.57,1:06:15.08,Default,,0,0,0,,We want to have a balanced view of things\N—a good conscience.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:15.08,1:06:17.79,Default,,0,0,0,,So how can we be balanced
Dialogue: 0,1:06:17.79,1:06:21.62,Default,,0,0,0,,when determining\Nwhether something is right or wrong?
Dialogue: 0,1:06:21.62,1:06:24.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, in some cases, it’s easy;\Nthe Bible tells us.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:24.58,1:06:28.17,Default,,0,0,0,,But in other cases, there’s no clear answer.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:28.17,1:06:31.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s consider a scenario\Nwe touched on earlier
Dialogue: 0,1:06:31.26,1:06:33.39,Default,,0,0,0,,—the matter of entering a church.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:33.39,1:06:36.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, that may not be\Na problem where you live,
Dialogue: 0,1:06:36.43,1:06:39.35,Default,,0,0,0,,but in some places, it’s a real issue.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:39.35,1:06:42.85,Default,,0,0,0,,And remember, these talks\Nare for our worldwide brotherhood.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:42.85,1:06:45.31,Default,,0,0,0,,So we’re going to consider a subject
Dialogue: 0,1:06:45.31,1:06:49.15,Default,,0,0,0,,that will be a real problem\Nfor many to overcome,
Dialogue: 0,1:06:49.15,1:06:51.19,Default,,0,0,0,,and we hope that they will benefit from it.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:51.19,1:06:53.20,Default,,0,0,0,,So here’s the scenario:
Dialogue: 0,1:06:53.20,1:06:57.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Two different sisters are married\Nto men who are not in the truth.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:57.28,1:07:01.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, in both cases,\Nthe husband’s mother has died.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:01.83,1:07:04.50,Default,,0,0,0,,The funeral will be in a church.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:04.50,1:07:06.92,Default,,0,0,0,,One sister decides to go;
Dialogue: 0,1:07:06.92,1:07:10.17,Default,,0,0,0,,the other decides against it.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:10.17,1:07:12.63,Default,,0,0,0,,The sister who decides to attend
Dialogue: 0,1:07:12.63,1:07:14.84,Default,,0,0,0,,has considered that in that church,
Dialogue: 0,1:07:14.84,1:07:17.51,Default,,0,0,0,,there will just be a talk by a clergyman.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:17.51,1:07:19.60,Default,,0,0,0,,There will be no congregation singing,
Dialogue: 0,1:07:19.60,1:07:22.85,Default,,0,0,0,,congregation prayers, or religious gestures.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:22.85,1:07:24.98,Default,,0,0,0,,She was never very religious anyway,
Dialogue: 0,1:07:24.98,1:07:27.19,Default,,0,0,0,,so none of that would mean anything to her.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:27.19,1:07:30.28,Default,,0,0,0,,And her husband and his family will be happy
Dialogue: 0,1:07:30.28,1:07:33.95,Default,,0,0,0,,if she just sits quietly until it’s over.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:35.36,1:07:38.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, the second sister\Nhas a different set of circumstances.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:38.70,1:07:43.29,Default,,0,0,0,,The service in that church\Ninvolves participation by the congregation.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:43.29,1:07:45.96,Default,,0,0,0,,She used to be\Nan active member of that church,
Dialogue: 0,1:07:45.96,1:07:49.84,Default,,0,0,0,,and she’s afraid\Nshe’ll do something she’ll regret.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:49.84,1:07:53.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Her husband’s family\Nget very emotional at funerals,
Dialogue: 0,1:07:53.63,1:07:57.18,Default,,0,0,0,,and they’re likely to make a scene\Nif she doesn’t participate.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:57.18,1:08:01.51,Default,,0,0,0,,So she respectfully tells her husband\Nthat her attendance
Dialogue: 0,1:08:01.51,1:08:05.98,Default,,0,0,0,,could cause him embarrassment\Nand declines to attend.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:05.98,1:08:10.61,Default,,0,0,0,,You can see that each situation is different.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:10.61,1:08:15.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Now we’re going to discuss four questions\Nthat we might ask ourselves
Dialogue: 0,1:08:15.49,1:08:19.03,Default,,0,0,0,,when we’re called upon\Nto make any difficult decision.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:19.03,1:08:22.87,Default,,0,0,0,,And I will repeat the question
Dialogue: 0,1:08:22.87,1:08:24.87,Default,,0,0,0,,because if you’re taking notes,
Dialogue: 0,1:08:24.87,1:08:27.50,Default,,0,0,0,,you may want to at least\Nwrite the question down.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:27.50,1:08:30.96,Default,,0,0,0,,These are very, very good questions\Nthat we can ask ourselves
Dialogue: 0,1:08:30.96,1:08:33.17,Default,,0,0,0,,before we make a difficult decision.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:33.17,1:08:34.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you ready?
Dialogue: 0,1:08:34.30,1:08:36.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Here’s number one:
Dialogue: 0,1:08:36.30,1:08:41.05,Default,,0,0,0,,What will make Jehovah happy?
Dialogue: 0,1:08:41.05,1:08:43.06,Default,,0,0,0,,I’ll repeat that.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:43.06,1:08:47.81,Default,,0,0,0,,What will make Jehovah happy?
Dialogue: 0,1:08:47.81,1:08:52.23,Default,,0,0,0,,And that should be our main concern,\Nto please Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:52.23,1:08:55.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, how do we know\Nwhat will make Jehovah happy?
Dialogue: 0,1:08:55.28,1:08:59.36,Default,,0,0,0,,We identify the Bible principles\Nthat have a bearing on the situation.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:59.36,1:09:01.37,Default,,0,0,0,,One way we can do that
Dialogue: 0,1:09:01.37,1:09:05.33,Default,,0,0,0,,is by checking the {\i1}{\fs16}{\fnArial}Index{\r}\Nor the {\i1}{\fs16}{\fnArial}Research Guide.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:05.33,1:09:07.71,Default,,0,0,0,,What are some Scriptural principles
Dialogue: 0,1:09:07.71,1:09:11.00,Default,,0,0,0,,a sister who’s married to an unbeliever\Nmight consider when deciding
Dialogue: 0,1:09:11.00,1:09:14.21,Default,,0,0,0,,whether to attend a funeral in a church?
Dialogue: 0,1:09:14.21,1:09:16.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Can you think of some?
Dialogue: 0,1:09:16.21,1:09:19.09,Default,,0,0,0,,What about 1 Peter 3:1?
Dialogue: 0,1:09:19.09,1:09:22.51,Default,,0,0,0,,“Wives, be in subjection to your husbands.”
Dialogue: 0,1:09:22.51,1:09:26.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah is pleased when\Na Christian woman respects her husband,
Dialogue: 0,1:09:26.35,1:09:28.56,Default,,0,0,0,,whether he’s in the truth or not.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:28.56,1:09:32.98,Default,,0,0,0,,But a wife’s subjection is relative.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:32.98,1:09:35.90,Default,,0,0,0,,She’s dedicated to Jehovah,
Dialogue: 0,1:09:35.90,1:09:38.70,Default,,0,0,0,,not to her husband.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:38.70,1:09:41.57,Default,,0,0,0,,She’s dedicated to Jehovah,
Dialogue: 0,1:09:41.57,1:09:44.58,Default,,0,0,0,,not to her husband.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:44.58,1:09:47.12,Default,,0,0,0,,So that’s 1 Peter 3:1.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:47.12,1:09:51.04,Default,,0,0,0,,What about Isaiah 52:11?
Dialogue: 0,1:09:51.04,1:09:53.59,Default,,0,0,0,,“Touch nothing unclean! . . .
Dialogue: 0,1:09:53.59,1:09:56.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Keep yourselves clean.”
Dialogue: 0,1:09:56.71,1:09:58.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Under the Mosaic Law,
Dialogue: 0,1:09:58.76,1:10:01.68,Default,,0,0,0,,if someone so much as\Ntouched something unclean,
Dialogue: 0,1:10:01.68,1:10:04.47,Default,,0,0,0,,he became unclean.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:04.47,1:10:08.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Many brothers and sisters\Nwould find it very hard to sit quietly
Dialogue: 0,1:10:08.64,1:10:11.94,Default,,0,0,0,,while a clergyman told lies\Nabout the condition of the dead.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:11.94,1:10:16.19,Default,,0,0,0,,To them, it would be\Ntouching something unclean.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:16.19,1:10:19.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Others might compare that\Nto a young person in school
Dialogue: 0,1:10:19.94,1:10:24.28,Default,,0,0,0,,sitting quietly while his teacher\Ntells lies about the origin of life.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:25.87,1:10:29.75,Default,,0,0,0,,If someone does decide\Nto attend a funeral in a church,
Dialogue: 0,1:10:29.75,1:10:33.04,Default,,0,0,0,,he or she should be absolutely determined
Dialogue: 0,1:10:33.04,1:10:36.38,Default,,0,0,0,,not to participate in any religious ritual,
Dialogue: 0,1:10:36.38,1:10:39.88,Default,,0,0,0,,whether singing hymns\Nor so much as saying “amen”
Dialogue: 0,1:10:39.88,1:10:42.30,Default,,0,0,0,,to a prayer that the clergyman offers.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:42.30,1:10:46.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Remember, the goal is to please Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:46.35,1:10:48.89,Default,,0,0,0,,So the first point was,
Dialogue: 0,1:10:48.89,1:10:51.81,Default,,0,0,0,,What makes Jehovah happy?
Dialogue: 0,1:10:51.81,1:10:54.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Number two—number two:
Dialogue: 0,1:10:54.69,1:10:58.78,Default,,0,0,0,,How might my choice affect others?
Dialogue: 0,1:10:59.82,1:11:01.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Have you got that?
Dialogue: 0,1:11:01.82,1:11:04.66,Default,,0,0,0,,How might my choice
Dialogue: 0,1:11:04.66,1:11:07.91,Default,,0,0,0,,affect others?
Dialogue: 0,1:11:07.91,1:11:10.41,Default,,0,0,0,,We would never want to stumble anyone.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:10.41,1:11:12.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Even in a family matter,
Dialogue: 0,1:11:12.41,1:11:15.33,Default,,0,0,0,,such as attending a wedding\Nor a funeral in a church
Dialogue: 0,1:11:15.33,1:11:17.96,Default,,0,0,0,,(which we may consider as a personal matter),
Dialogue: 0,1:11:17.96,1:11:20.67,Default,,0,0,0,,we need to weigh the effect our decision
Dialogue: 0,1:11:20.67,1:11:23.42,Default,,0,0,0,,could have on others.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:23.42,1:11:26.39,Default,,0,0,0,,It could affect them in one of two ways.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:26.39,1:11:28.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, the first is the obvious way.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:28.76,1:11:32.64,Default,,0,0,0,,In some areas, if a Witness\Neven entered a church,
Dialogue: 0,1:11:32.64,1:11:36.19,Default,,0,0,0,,his brothers and sisters\Nwould lose respect for him.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:36.19,1:11:39.86,Default,,0,0,0,,But there’s a second way\Nthe Witness could stumble someone.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:39.86,1:11:44.03,Default,,0,0,0,,He might be able to attend the funeral\Nand make no compromise.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:44.03,1:11:46.36,Default,,0,0,0,,But suppose a new brother decided
Dialogue: 0,1:11:46.36,1:11:49.37,Default,,0,0,0,,to follow his example\Nwhen a family member died.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:49.37,1:11:51.95,Default,,0,0,0,,The new brother could give in\Nto family pressure
Dialogue: 0,1:11:51.95,1:11:54.50,Default,,0,0,0,,and participate in idolatry.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:54.50,1:11:57.38,Default,,0,0,0,,How tragic is that!
Dialogue: 0,1:11:57.38,1:12:00.13,Default,,0,0,0,,The apostle Paul never worshipped idols.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:00.13,1:12:04.88,Default,,0,0,0,,So when meat that had been offered to an idol\Nwent up for sale in a meat market,
Dialogue: 0,1:12:04.88,1:12:08.01,Default,,0,0,0,,it probably didn’t bother\NPaul’s conscience to buy it
Dialogue: 0,1:12:08.01,1:12:10.76,Default,,0,0,0,,because he knew that an idol is nothing.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:10.76,1:12:14.02,Default,,0,0,0,,But some of his brothers had worshipped
Dialogue: 0,1:12:14.02,1:12:17.23,Default,,0,0,0,,those very idols\Nbefore coming into the truth.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:17.23,1:12:20.11,Default,,0,0,0,,They could have felt guilty\Nabout eating that meat.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:20.11,1:12:24.53,Default,,0,0,0,,To them, it would be\Nlike having a communion meal with an idol.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:26.61,1:12:30.37,Default,,0,0,0,,The feelings of his brothers\Nwere important to Paul.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:30.37,1:12:33.41,Default,,0,0,0,,He was willing to sacrifice his own rights
Dialogue: 0,1:12:33.41,1:12:36.29,Default,,0,0,0,,for the sake of his brothers.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:36.29,1:12:38.79,Default,,0,0,0,,We’d never want to take the unloving view
Dialogue: 0,1:12:38.79,1:12:41.34,Default,,0,0,0,,that if our brother\Nis stumbled by what we do,
Dialogue: 0,1:12:41.34,1:12:43.59,Default,,0,0,0,,it’s too bad for him.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:43.59,1:12:45.59,Default,,0,0,0,,On the other hand,
Dialogue: 0,1:12:45.59,1:12:50.35,Default,,0,0,0,,if we’re the type of person\Nwho is often stumbled by what others do,
Dialogue: 0,1:12:50.35,1:12:54.60,Default,,0,0,0,,we need to ask Jehovah\Nto help us gain a more balanced viewpoint.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:56.89,1:13:00.65,Default,,0,0,0,,So far, we’ve discussed\Nthe need to make Jehovah happy
Dialogue: 0,1:13:00.65,1:13:03.23,Default,,0,0,0,,and to consider the feelings of our brothers.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:03.23,1:13:04.69,Default,,0,0,0,,What’s next?
Dialogue: 0,1:13:04.69,1:13:09.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Number three: Have I asked for counsel?
Dialogue: 0,1:13:10.62,1:13:12.24,Default,,0,0,0,,You got that?
Dialogue: 0,1:13:12.24,1:13:16.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Have I asked for counsel?
Dialogue: 0,1:13:16.12,1:13:20.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, maybe the elders haven’t dealt\Nwith the exact situation we’re facing,
Dialogue: 0,1:13:20.38,1:13:22.25,Default,,0,0,0,,but they know a lot of people.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:22.25,1:13:26.01,Default,,0,0,0,,They may know someone\Nwho has dealt with the situation before
Dialogue: 0,1:13:26.01,1:13:28.05,Default,,0,0,0,,and saw how he handled it.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:28.05,1:13:31.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Or they may know about the effect\Nthe decision had on others.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:31.89,1:13:35.18,Default,,0,0,0,,For example, they might know\Nhow the congregation reacted
Dialogue: 0,1:13:35.18,1:13:38.60,Default,,0,0,0,,the last time someone attended a wedding
Dialogue: 0,1:13:38.60,1:13:40.85,Default,,0,0,0,,or a funeral in a church.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:42.61,1:13:46.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Another situation where brothers often ask\Nfor the help of the elders
Dialogue: 0,1:13:46.53,1:13:50.07,Default,,0,0,0,,involves the use of blood fractions.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:50.07,1:13:53.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Should we accept them or not?
Dialogue: 0,1:13:53.32,1:13:58.16,Default,,0,0,0,,The Governing Body has refused\Nto impose its conscience on the brotherhood.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:58.16,1:13:59.41,Default,,0,0,0,,But what do we know?
Dialogue: 0,1:13:59.41,1:14:04.09,Default,,0,0,0,,We know that the Bible says\Nto “abstain . . . from blood.”
Dialogue: 0,1:14:04.09,1:14:07.13,Default,,0,0,0,,But as you divide it into fractions
Dialogue: 0,1:14:07.13,1:14:10.38,Default,,0,0,0,,and the fractions get tinier and tinier,
Dialogue: 0,1:14:10.38,1:14:15.14,Default,,0,0,0,,at what point does blood stop being blood?
Dialogue: 0,1:14:15.14,1:14:18.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Each one will have to decide that\Nfor himself.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:18.43,1:14:19.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, some might say,
Dialogue: 0,1:14:19.85,1:14:22.19,Default,,0,0,0,,“Well, if it’s a really,\Nreally tiny fraction,
Dialogue: 0,1:14:22.19,1:14:24.06,Default,,0,0,0,,it doesn’t bother me to take it.”
Dialogue: 0,1:14:24.06,1:14:26.27,Default,,0,0,0,,But others will say:\N“It doesn’t matter to me.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:26.27,1:14:29.82,Default,,0,0,0,,If it’s from blood, I don’t want it.”
Dialogue: 0,1:14:29.82,1:14:34.12,Default,,0,0,0,,And their conscience\Nalso has to be respected.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:34.12,1:14:36.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let’s illustrate:
Dialogue: 0,1:14:36.24,1:14:39.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Air is made up of nitrogen
Dialogue: 0,1:14:39.91,1:14:41.91,Default,,0,0,0,,and oxygen,
Dialogue: 0,1:14:41.91,1:14:46.92,Default,,0,0,0,,and together they make up 99 percent of air.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:46.92,1:14:49.55,Default,,0,0,0,,That leaves 1 percent.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:49.55,1:14:53.09,Default,,0,0,0,,The 1 percent is made up\Nof a variety of gases:
Dialogue: 0,1:14:53.09,1:14:56.93,Default,,0,0,0,,carbon dioxide, hydrogen, neon
Dialogue: 0,1:14:56.93,1:15:00.18,Default,,0,0,0,,—small fractions.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:00.18,1:15:02.23,Default,,0,0,0,,When it comes to small fractions,
Dialogue: 0,1:15:02.23,1:15:04.23,Default,,0,0,0,,elders need to be careful, though,
Dialogue: 0,1:15:04.23,1:15:07.94,Default,,0,0,0,,not to insert their personal opinion\Ninto the discussion,
Dialogue: 0,1:15:07.94,1:15:11.19,Default,,0,0,0,,such as by saying\N“I wouldn’t take any of it.”
Dialogue: 0,1:15:11.19,1:15:15.37,Default,,0,0,0,,They should simply help the publisher\Nto reason on the basic principles
Dialogue: 0,1:15:15.37,1:15:18.41,Default,,0,0,0,,and let him make up his own mind.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:18.41,1:15:20.50,Default,,0,0,0,,So where are we?
Dialogue: 0,1:15:20.50,1:15:22.12,Default,,0,0,0,,We make Jehovah happy.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:22.12,1:15:25.29,Default,,0,0,0,,We consider the feelings\Nof our brothers and sisters.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:25.29,1:15:27.29,Default,,0,0,0,,We ask for counsel.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:27.29,1:15:29.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Number four:
Dialogue: 0,1:15:29.30,1:15:32.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Did I take the time
Dialogue: 0,1:15:33.59,1:15:36.26,Default,,0,0,0,,—did I take the time—
Dialogue: 0,1:15:36.26,1:15:40.64,Default,,0,0,0,,to meditate prayerfully\Nbefore making my decision?
Dialogue: 0,1:15:42.06,1:15:46.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Did I take the time to meditate prayerfully
Dialogue: 0,1:15:46.06,1:15:48.86,Default,,0,0,0,,before making my decision?
Dialogue: 0,1:15:48.86,1:15:52.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Your goal is to make Jehovah happy.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:52.07,1:15:54.53,Default,,0,0,0,,So you wouldn’t want\Nto make your decision hastily
Dialogue: 0,1:15:54.53,1:15:56.61,Default,,0,0,0,,and then ask Jehovah to bless it.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:56.61,1:15:59.66,Default,,0,0,0,,We should ask Jehovah for guidance first
Dialogue: 0,1:15:59.66,1:16:02.41,Default,,0,0,0,,rather than asking him to bless a decision
Dialogue: 0,1:16:02.41,1:16:05.00,Default,,0,0,0,,we’ve already made.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:05.00,1:16:07.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Have you ever heard someone say,
Dialogue: 0,1:16:07.13,1:16:09.88,Default,,0,0,0,,“That doesn’t bother my conscience”?
Dialogue: 0,1:16:09.88,1:16:14.42,Default,,0,0,0,,We might ask:\N‘How did he come to that conclusion?
Dialogue: 0,1:16:14.42,1:16:18.09,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Did he follow the four steps\Nwe just mentioned?
Dialogue: 0,1:16:18.09,1:16:22.01,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Did he do research to learn\Nwhat makes Jehovah happy?
Dialogue: 0,1:16:22.01,1:16:24.85,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Did he think\Nabout how others might be affected?
Dialogue: 0,1:16:24.85,1:16:26.85,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Did he ask for counsel?
Dialogue: 0,1:16:26.85,1:16:30.40,Default,,0,0,0,,‘And did he meditate prayerfully\Non his decision?
Dialogue: 0,1:16:30.40,1:16:35.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Or is he just following his feelings?’
Dialogue: 0,1:16:35.07,1:16:38.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Following your feelings isn’t the same
Dialogue: 0,1:16:38.41,1:16:42.03,Default,,0,0,0,,as following a Bible-trained conscience.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:42.03,1:16:43.45,Default,,0,0,0,,I’m going to repeat that.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:43.45,1:16:47.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Following your feelings is not the same
Dialogue: 0,1:16:47.21,1:16:51.67,Default,,0,0,0,,as following a Bible-trained conscience.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:51.67,1:16:54.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Our conscience needs to be trained
Dialogue: 0,1:16:54.17,1:16:56.72,Default,,0,0,0,,in harmony with Scriptural principles.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:56.72,1:16:59.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, Paul’s conscience\Ndidn’t bother him a bit
Dialogue: 0,1:16:59.72,1:17:01.72,Default,,0,0,0,,when he was persecuting Christians.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:01.72,1:17:04.27,Default,,0,0,0,,He thought he was doing Jehovah a favor.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:04.27,1:17:07.19,Default,,0,0,0,,But when he realized\Nhow Jehovah felt about it,
Dialogue: 0,1:17:07.19,1:17:09.48,Default,,0,0,0,,he knew he had to change.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:09.48,1:17:14.36,Default,,0,0,0,,We have to be sure that we’re really getting\NJehovah’s thinking on matters.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:14.36,1:17:17.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Remember Jeremiah 17:9
Dialogue: 0,1:17:20.16,1:17:23.78,Default,,0,0,0,,—simple expression but so true.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:23.78,1:17:28.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Jeremiah chapter 17
Dialogue: 0,1:17:28.16,1:17:30.17,Default,,0,0,0,,and verse 9 says:
Dialogue: 0,1:17:32.79,1:17:36.17,Default,,0,0,0,,“The heart is more treacherous
Dialogue: 0,1:17:36.17,1:17:39.51,Default,,0,0,0,,“than anything else and is desperate.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:39.51,1:17:41.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Who can know it?”
Dialogue: 0,1:17:43.51,1:17:47.43,Default,,0,0,0,,‘The heart is treacherous.’
Dialogue: 0,1:17:47.43,1:17:50.65,Default,,0,0,0,,We might allow our emotions\Nto get the better of us.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:50.65,1:17:54.15,Default,,0,0,0,,For example, when a family member\Nis disfellowshipped,
Dialogue: 0,1:17:54.15,1:17:56.36,Default,,0,0,0,,if the person is living outside the home,
Dialogue: 0,1:17:56.36,1:17:58.44,Default,,0,0,0,,we know that we should limit our association
Dialogue: 0,1:17:58.44,1:18:01.45,Default,,0,0,0,,to necessary family business.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:01.45,1:18:05.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, if the family was never very close,\Nthat might not be a problem.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:05.54,1:18:09.46,Default,,0,0,0,,But suppose family ties are really strong;
Dialogue: 0,1:18:09.46,1:18:11.75,Default,,0,0,0,,that can be a challenge.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:11.75,1:18:14.92,Default,,0,0,0,,If we allow ourselves to be ruled by emotion
Dialogue: 0,1:18:14.92,1:18:17.51,Default,,0,0,0,,rather than by Scriptural principles,
Dialogue: 0,1:18:17.51,1:18:21.59,Default,,0,0,0,,we could stretch the meaning\Nof necessary family business
Dialogue: 0,1:18:21.59,1:18:24.85,Default,,0,0,0,,to include almost any activity.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:24.85,1:18:27.85,Default,,0,0,0,,The heart is treacherous.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:28.98,1:18:32.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Asking ourselves\Nthe four questions we just mentioned
Dialogue: 0,1:18:32.19,1:18:36.02,Default,,0,0,0,,can help us to make decisions\Nbased on godly principles
Dialogue: 0,1:18:36.02,1:18:40.36,Default,,0,0,0,,rather than simply relying on our feelings.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:40.36,1:18:43.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let’s see how mature Christians
Dialogue: 0,1:18:43.28,1:18:47.16,Default,,0,0,0,,can apply these principles\Nand how the elders can help.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:48.54,1:18:50.66,Default,,0,0,0,,The following video interviews
Dialogue: 0,1:18:50.66,1:18:53.75,Default,,0,0,0,,are about weddings and funerals
Dialogue: 0,1:18:53.75,1:18:57.71,Default,,0,0,0,,—a touchy subject\Nin many cultures, as you will see.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:02.59,1:19:04.59,Default,,0,0,0,,In Japan,
Dialogue: 0,1:19:04.59,1:19:08.22,Default,,0,0,0,,religious rituals are associated\Nwith each stage of life
Dialogue: 0,1:19:08.22,1:19:10.35,Default,,0,0,0,,and with each season of the year.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:11.77,1:19:13.77,Default,,0,0,0,,As Jehovah’s Witnesses,
Dialogue: 0,1:19:13.77,1:19:16.52,Default,,0,0,0,,we want to keep the cleanliness and unity
Dialogue: 0,1:19:16.52,1:19:19.19,Default,,0,0,0,,of the congregation.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:19.19,1:19:22.61,Default,,0,0,0,,In this regard,\None of the most delicate areas
Dialogue: 0,1:19:22.61,1:19:27.20,Default,,0,0,0,,is the decision on whether to attend\Na non-Witness funeral or not.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:29.58,1:19:33.79,Default,,0,0,0,,The first thing we must consider\Nregarding funerals is not to be involved
Dialogue: 0,1:19:33.79,1:19:38.04,Default,,0,0,0,,in religious rituals and acts of worship\Nthat are condemned by the Bible.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:39.84,1:19:41.46,Default,,0,0,0,,In harmony with the principle
Dialogue: 0,1:19:41.46,1:19:44.84,Default,,0,0,0,,at 2 Corinthians 6:14,
Dialogue: 0,1:19:44.84,1:19:47.01,Default,,0,0,0,,we need to keep completely separate
Dialogue: 0,1:19:47.01,1:19:48.51,Default,,0,0,0,,from pagan acts of worship.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:50.72,1:19:55.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Next, even if we don’t participate\Nin the worship of other religions,
Dialogue: 0,1:19:55.60,1:20:00.36,Default,,0,0,0,,we need to consider if our decisions\Ncould stumble someone in the congregation.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:02.36,1:20:04.57,Default,,0,0,0,,When we consider the Bible principle
Dialogue: 0,1:20:04.57,1:20:07.28,Default,,0,0,0,,at Luke 17:2,
Dialogue: 0,1:20:07.28,1:20:09.62,Default,,0,0,0,,we do not want our decisions to hinder
Dialogue: 0,1:20:09.62,1:20:11.83,Default,,0,0,0,,the faith of someone in the congregation.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:16.50,1:20:20.42,Default,,0,0,0,,The third point to think about\Nis our conscience.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:21.34,1:20:23.34,Default,,0,0,0,,We need to seriously think
Dialogue: 0,1:20:23.34,1:20:24.76,Default,,0,0,0,,about the Bible principle
Dialogue: 0,1:20:24.76,1:20:28.26,Default,,0,0,0,,at Galatians 6:5, where it says
Dialogue: 0,1:20:28.26,1:20:31.14,Default,,0,0,0,,that each must “carry his own load.”
Dialogue: 0,1:20:33.39,1:20:36.85,Default,,0,0,0,,This Bible principle also applies\Nwhen elders want to support others.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:38.10,1:20:42.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course, those in the congregation\Ncan ask the elders for support
Dialogue: 0,1:20:42.73,1:20:45.15,Default,,0,0,0,,in issues related to funerals.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:46.36,1:20:48.61,Default,,0,0,0,,However, in matters of conscience,
Dialogue: 0,1:20:48.61,1:20:51.78,Default,,0,0,0,,elders cannot force decisions on others.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:53.54,1:20:57.42,Default,,0,0,0,,So it would be wrong to make\Nsome kind of rule regarding attending
Dialogue: 0,1:20:57.42,1:20:59.08,Default,,0,0,0,,non-Witness funerals.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:00.67,1:21:02.04,Default,,0,0,0,,If each person can make
Dialogue: 0,1:21:02.04,1:21:04.59,Default,,0,0,0,,decisions based on Bible principles,
Dialogue: 0,1:21:04.59,1:21:06.59,Default,,0,0,0,,we can have a truly peaceful
Dialogue: 0,1:21:06.59,1:21:08.59,Default,,0,0,0,,and free atmosphere
Dialogue: 0,1:21:08.59,1:21:10.47,Default,,0,0,0,,where each individual’s
Dialogue: 0,1:21:10.47,1:21:13.10,Default,,0,0,0,,differing situation is respected.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:14.47,1:21:18.56,Default,,0,0,0,,This would really contribute\Nto the unity of the congregation.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:18.56,1:21:21.19,Default,,0,0,0,,And all can maintain a clean conscience
Dialogue: 0,1:21:21.19,1:21:23.82,Default,,0,0,0,,and serve happily before Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:26.65,1:21:28.53,Default,,0,0,0,,In my culture,
Dialogue: 0,1:21:28.53,1:21:31.24,Default,,0,0,0,,specifically the Namibian Oshiwambo\Nculture,
Dialogue: 0,1:21:31.24,1:21:33.74,Default,,0,0,0,,like in many African cultures,
Dialogue: 0,1:21:33.74,1:21:38.08,Default,,0,0,0,,there are many spiritistic customs\Nrelated to weddings
Dialogue: 0,1:21:38.08,1:21:40.83,Default,,0,0,0,,that are included in wedding celebrations.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:40.83,1:21:43.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Unfortunately, my family is not in the truth.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:43.13,1:21:44.63,Default,,0,0,0,,So obviously, for Ben and I,
Dialogue: 0,1:21:44.63,1:21:47.51,Default,,0,0,0,,that was one of the main concerns.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:47.51,1:21:50.09,Default,,0,0,0,,They don’t understand our worship of Jehovah,
Dialogue: 0,1:21:50.09,1:21:52.64,Default,,0,0,0,,and they don’t understand\Nthat we apply Bible principles
Dialogue: 0,1:21:52.64,1:21:54.76,Default,,0,0,0,,and not the traditions of men.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:54.76,1:21:57.48,Default,,0,0,0,,We got engaged before the pandemic,
Dialogue: 0,1:21:57.48,1:22:00.85,Default,,0,0,0,,but obviously, now that our wedding\Nwas to be over videoconferencing,
Dialogue: 0,1:22:00.85,1:22:04.02,Default,,0,0,0,,it meant that we didn’t have control\Nover many things.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:04.02,1:22:06.32,Default,,0,0,0,,We tried to imagine situations
Dialogue: 0,1:22:06.32,1:22:08.32,Default,,0,0,0,,that could stumble our brothers or disrupt
Dialogue: 0,1:22:08.32,1:22:10.36,Default,,0,0,0,,the unity in the congregation.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:12.91,1:22:15.03,Default,,0,0,0,,We had to, in advance,
Dialogue: 0,1:22:15.03,1:22:17.87,Default,,0,0,0,,think of Bible principles\Nthat would apply in our case,
Dialogue: 0,1:22:17.87,1:22:22.54,Default,,0,0,0,,but particularly what we also found helpful\Nwas speaking to a mature elder.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:22.54,1:22:26.67,Default,,0,0,0,,He gave us a principle at Proverbs 14:15.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:27.88,1:22:30.88,Default,,0,0,0,,He told us to be very careful\Nwhen people say,
Dialogue: 0,1:22:30.88,1:22:34.05,Default,,0,0,0,,“I will do this” or “I won’t do this”\Nat your wedding.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:34.05,1:22:38.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Basically, it was up to us to make sure\Nthat the proceedings
Dialogue: 0,1:22:38.81,1:22:40.81,Default,,0,0,0,,or things that happen at our wedding
Dialogue: 0,1:22:40.81,1:22:44.61,Default,,0,0,0,,would be in order and in harmony\Nwith Bible principles.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:44.61,1:22:46.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Another principle that came to mind was
Dialogue: 0,1:22:46.77,1:22:50.19,Default,,0,0,0,,1 Corinthians 10:23.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:50.19,1:22:54.24,Default,,0,0,0,,So obviously, we knew\Nthat we had the right to do many things,
Dialogue: 0,1:22:54.24,1:22:56.28,Default,,0,0,0,,but we were also very conscious
Dialogue: 0,1:22:56.28,1:22:59.75,Default,,0,0,0,,of how our brothers would view our wedding.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:59.75,1:23:03.83,Default,,0,0,0,,We didn’t want anybody to be at our wedding\Nand feel embarrassed
Dialogue: 0,1:23:03.83,1:23:06.17,Default,,0,0,0,,or even stumbled to be there.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:07.17,1:23:09.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Now looking back at our wedding,
Dialogue: 0,1:23:09.88,1:23:12.34,Default,,0,0,0,,we look back with fond memories.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:13.30,1:23:18.06,Default,,0,0,0,,So applying Bible principles\Ndidn’t restrict our fun.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:19.68,1:23:22.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Also, it contributed to the unity\Namong our brothers
Dialogue: 0,1:23:22.31,1:23:25.02,Default,,0,0,0,,because all of us\N—those present, those who were invited—
Dialogue: 0,1:23:25.02,1:23:27.15,Default,,0,0,0,,were able to enjoy the wedding.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:27.15,1:23:30.36,Default,,0,0,0,,You’re not worried about thinking,\N‘Oh, did that thing offend anybody?’
Dialogue: 0,1:23:30.36,1:23:34.95,Default,,0,0,0,,So you’re able to enjoy the day\Nwithout any bad memories.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:40.45,1:23:43.96,Default,,0,0,0,,As you can see,\Nour brothers in many countries
Dialogue: 0,1:23:43.96,1:23:46.25,Default,,0,0,0,,are faced with very difficult decisions
Dialogue: 0,1:23:46.25,1:23:48.92,Default,,0,0,0,,where weddings and funerals are concerned.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:48.92,1:23:53.92,Default,,0,0,0,,The guidance the elders\Ncan provide is invaluable.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:53.92,1:23:56.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, sometimes medical doctors
Dialogue: 0,1:23:56.34,1:23:59.39,Default,,0,0,0,,complain that their Witness patients\Nare inconsistent
Dialogue: 0,1:23:59.39,1:24:03.39,Default,,0,0,0,,because they don’t all have the same view\Nof certain medical treatments.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:03.39,1:24:06.85,Default,,0,0,0,,One Witness patient\Naccepts certain fractions or therapies,
Dialogue: 0,1:24:06.85,1:24:10.77,Default,,0,0,0,,so the doctor figures he knows\Nwhat Jehovah’s Witnesses believe.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:10.77,1:24:13.49,Default,,0,0,0,,But then the next patient comes along,
Dialogue: 0,1:24:13.49,1:24:15.57,Default,,0,0,0,,and he rejects them all.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:15.57,1:24:18.24,Default,,0,0,0,,The doctor is confused.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:18.24,1:24:21.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Those doctors don’t understand\Nthe role of the conscience.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:21.79,1:24:24.41,Default,,0,0,0,,We shouldn’t worry\Nwhen medical professionals
Dialogue: 0,1:24:24.41,1:24:26.42,Default,,0,0,0,,don’t understand our differing viewpoints,
Dialogue: 0,1:24:26.42,1:24:29.17,Default,,0,0,0,,because we should be glad\Nthat we serve a God
Dialogue: 0,1:24:29.17,1:24:32.17,Default,,0,0,0,,who dignifies us\Nwith the freedom to make many
Dialogue: 0,1:24:32.17,1:24:34.21,Default,,0,0,0,,of our own decisions.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:35.93,1:24:38.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, the apostle Paul\Nmentioned four qualities
Dialogue: 0,1:24:38.55,1:24:42.10,Default,,0,0,0,,that will help us to maintain\Nthe uniting bond of peace.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:42.10,1:24:44.10,Default,,0,0,0,,And we’re going to find those qualities
Dialogue: 0,1:24:44.10,1:24:46.14,Default,,0,0,0,,at Ephesians chapter 4,
Dialogue: 0,1:24:46.14,1:24:49.73,Default,,0,0,0,,and we’re going to zero in on verse 2.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:49.73,1:24:53.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s turn to Ephesians chapter 4,
Dialogue: 0,1:24:53.44,1:24:55.53,Default,,0,0,0,,and we’re going to look at verse 2.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:55.53,1:24:58.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, we read verses 3-6 earlier,
Dialogue: 0,1:24:58.57,1:25:01.28,Default,,0,0,0,,and you know that Paul\Nwas concerned about unity.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:01.28,1:25:03.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Unity is what he had on his mind,
Dialogue: 0,1:25:03.49,1:25:07.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and now he is telling us\Nthat these four qualities
Dialogue: 0,1:25:07.00,1:25:10.71,Default,,0,0,0,,are going to help us to maintain our unity.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:10.71,1:25:12.71,Default,,0,0,0,,“Earnestly endeavoring”
Dialogue: 0,1:25:12.71,1:25:15.34,Default,,0,0,0,,—remember when he said\N“earnestly endeavoring
Dialogue: 0,1:25:15.34,1:25:18.26,Default,,0,0,0,,to maintain the oneness of the spirit”?
Dialogue: 0,1:25:18.26,1:25:22.55,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s the work that we need\Nto put into promoting unity.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:22.55,1:25:24.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Verse 2 says:
Dialogue: 0,1:25:24.56,1:25:29.56,Default,,0,0,0,,“With all humility and mildness,
Dialogue: 0,1:25:29.56,1:25:32.40,Default,,0,0,0,,“with patience,
Dialogue: 0,1:25:32.40,1:25:36.74,Default,,0,0,0,,putting up with one another in love.”
Dialogue: 0,1:25:36.74,1:25:38.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Isn’t that beautiful?
Dialogue: 0,1:25:38.11,1:25:42.74,Default,,0,0,0,,You notice the qualities:\Nhumility, mildness,
Dialogue: 0,1:25:42.74,1:25:45.70,Default,,0,0,0,,patience, and love?
Dialogue: 0,1:25:45.70,1:25:47.71,Default,,0,0,0,,When we’re humble,
Dialogue: 0,1:25:47.71,1:25:51.88,Default,,0,0,0,,we recognize that our opinion\Nisn’t always the right one.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:51.88,1:25:54.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Humility will also prevent us
Dialogue: 0,1:25:54.04,1:25:56.59,Default,,0,0,0,,from trying to impose\Nour conscience on others
Dialogue: 0,1:25:56.59,1:26:01.18,Default,,0,0,0,,as if Jehovah had appointed us to judge them.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:01.18,1:26:03.68,Default,,0,0,0,,What about mildness?
Dialogue: 0,1:26:03.68,1:26:07.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Mildness will help us to think\Nabout the effect our words might have
Dialogue: 0,1:26:07.22,1:26:09.27,Default,,0,0,0,,on our brothers and sisters.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:09.27,1:26:11.27,Default,,0,0,0,,We would never want to hurt them,
Dialogue: 0,1:26:11.27,1:26:14.61,Default,,0,0,0,,even when we strongly disagree with them.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:14.61,1:26:17.82,Default,,0,0,0,,And we should give them\Nthe benefit of the doubt.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:17.82,1:26:21.16,Default,,0,0,0,,If someone says something\Nthat makes you mad,
Dialogue: 0,1:26:21.16,1:26:24.24,Default,,0,0,0,,pray before you speak.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:25.49,1:26:29.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Pray before you speak.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:31.50,1:26:35.34,Default,,0,0,0,,“Love covers a multitude of sins,”
Dialogue: 0,1:26:35.34,1:26:38.63,Default,,0,0,0,,which contributes\Nto the peace of the congregation.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:38.63,1:26:42.34,Default,,0,0,0,,And we deeply appreciate it\Nwhen our brothers are patient with us.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:42.34,1:26:45.68,Default,,0,0,0,,In turn, we need to be patient with them
Dialogue: 0,1:26:45.68,1:26:50.31,Default,,0,0,0,,because we’re all\Nat different stages of spiritual growth,
Dialogue: 0,1:26:50.31,1:26:52.35,Default,,0,0,0,,and we have to acknowledge that.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:53.98,1:26:56.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we’ve talked\Nabout making Jehovah happy
Dialogue: 0,1:26:56.82,1:26:58.82,Default,,0,0,0,,with our decisions.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:58.82,1:27:01.24,Default,,0,0,0,,We can also please Jehovah\Nwhen we work hard
Dialogue: 0,1:27:01.24,1:27:03.91,Default,,0,0,0,,to promote peace in the congregation,
Dialogue: 0,1:27:03.91,1:27:06.95,Default,,0,0,0,,and sometimes it does take\Nan earnest endeavor.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:06.95,1:27:09.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Sometimes we have to work hard
Dialogue: 0,1:27:09.24,1:27:12.62,Default,,0,0,0,,at ensuring\Nthat the congregation is at peace.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:12.62,1:27:14.21,Default,,0,0,0,,What about the elders?
Dialogue: 0,1:27:14.21,1:27:19.05,Default,,0,0,0,,The elders take the lead\Nin working together in unity.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:19.05,1:27:22.59,Default,,0,0,0,,They should always speak with a united voice.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:22.59,1:27:26.47,Default,,0,0,0,,If they don’t, their congregation\Nwill sense that they’re divided,
Dialogue: 0,1:27:26.47,1:27:29.81,Default,,0,0,0,,and this will make\Nthe brothers and sisters uneasy.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:29.81,1:27:33.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Any difference of opinion\Nshould be worked out in private,
Dialogue: 0,1:27:33.64,1:27:37.65,Default,,0,0,0,,while showing deep respect for one another.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:37.65,1:27:42.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Just because someone disagrees with us\Ndoesn’t make him a bad person.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:42.03,1:27:44.03,Default,,0,0,0,,We have to understand that,
Dialogue: 0,1:27:44.03,1:27:48.66,Default,,0,0,0,,and his difference of opinion\Nmay search us through.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:48.66,1:27:51.54,Default,,0,0,0,,It may be something\Nthat we need to think about and consider.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:51.54,1:27:56.04,Default,,0,0,0,,And we always consider\Nthat the other person may be right.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:56.04,1:27:58.04,Default,,0,0,0,,What about us publishers?
Dialogue: 0,1:27:58.04,1:28:01.00,Default,,0,0,0,,If we’re having a hard time\Ngetting along with someone,
Dialogue: 0,1:28:01.00,1:28:03.72,Default,,0,0,0,,rather than asking Jehovah to change him,
Dialogue: 0,1:28:03.72,1:28:06.22,Default,,0,0,0,,we should ask Jehovah to mold us,
Dialogue: 0,1:28:06.22,1:28:08.51,Default,,0,0,0,,like the Great Potter he is.
Dialogue: 0,1:28:08.51,1:28:12.81,Default,,0,0,0,,We should ask him to show us\Nwhy he drew that person to the congregation.
Dialogue: 0,1:28:12.81,1:28:14.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Remember what Jesus said?
Dialogue: 0,1:28:14.60,1:28:18.65,Default,,0,0,0,,‘No one comes to him\Nunless the Father draws him.’
Dialogue: 0,1:28:18.65,1:28:21.48,Default,,0,0,0,,What does Jehovah see in that person
Dialogue: 0,1:28:21.48,1:28:23.78,Default,,0,0,0,,that we aren’t seeing?
Dialogue: 0,1:28:25.03,1:28:28.41,Default,,0,0,0,,We each have a responsibility to contribute
Dialogue: 0,1:28:28.41,1:28:31.54,Default,,0,0,0,,to the peace and unity of the congregation.
Dialogue: 0,1:28:31.54,1:28:35.83,Default,,0,0,0,,May Jehovah bless us\Nas we work toward that goal.
Dialogue: 0,1:28:37.67,1:28:41.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you, Brother Splane,\Nfor that motivating talk!
Dialogue: 0,1:28:41.50,1:28:44.21,Default,,0,0,0,,We are determined to do our part
Dialogue: 0,1:28:44.21,1:28:48.39,Default,,0,0,0,,to safeguard our “uniting bond of peace.”
Dialogue: 0,1:28:50.72,1:28:55.48,Default,,0,0,0,,This session has provided\Nsuch practical lessons!
Dialogue: 0,1:28:55.48,1:28:59.02,Default,,0,0,0,,What can we look forward to\Nin the next session?
Dialogue: 0,1:28:59.02,1:29:03.86,Default,,0,0,0,,The theme scripture will be Romans 15:13,
Dialogue: 0,1:29:03.86,1:29:05.86,Default,,0,0,0,,which says in part:
Dialogue: 0,1:29:05.86,1:29:08.24,Default,,0,0,0,,“May the God who gives hope
Dialogue: 0,1:29:08.24,1:29:12.62,Default,,0,0,0,,fill you with all joy and peace.”
Dialogue: 0,1:29:12.62,1:29:15.62,Default,,0,0,0,,The program will feature\Na seven-part symposium
Dialogue: 0,1:29:15.62,1:29:18.54,Default,,0,0,0,,with Bible examples of those who sowed
Dialogue: 0,1:29:18.54,1:29:21.17,Default,,0,0,0,,and reaped peace.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:21.17,1:29:24.13,Default,,0,0,0,,We will also want to invite\Nas many as possible
Dialogue: 0,1:29:24.13,1:29:27.80,Default,,0,0,0,,to enjoy the public Bible discourse entitled
Dialogue: 0,1:29:27.80,1:29:31.60,Default,,0,0,0,,“Friendship With God—How Possible?”
Dialogue: 0,1:29:33.51,1:29:37.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let’s sing together song number 113,
Dialogue: 0,1:29:37.85,1:29:42.15,Default,,0,0,0,,which draws attention to what it means\Nto have godly peace.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:42.15,1:29:44.19,Default,,0,0,0,,The song is entitled
Dialogue: 0,1:29:44.19,1:29:47.69,Default,,0,0,0,,“Our Possession of Peace.”
Dialogue: 0,1:29:47.69,1:29:52.41,Default,,0,0,0,,After the song, you may have\Nyour local concluding prayer.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:52.41,1:29:55.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Again, that’s song number 113.
